# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bat-and-ball-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] The 100-ball game has two teams each having a single innings, which is restricted to a maximum of 100 balls, and the match lasts approximately two and a half hours, shorter than the Twenty20 format.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] Before the launch of the professional The Hundred competition in July 2021, the 100-ball format was trialled in several amateur local leagues across England.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] The new 100-ball format was born out of a proposal by the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) in 2016 to launch a new franchise cricket competition, similar to the Indian Premier League.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] At first it was expected that the competition would use the existing Twenty20 format.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] Following discussions involving the ECB's marketing team, clubs were instead told in April 2018 that the competition would use an entirely new form of cricket designed to be simpler to follow and shorter to fit television schedules.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] The more detailed proposal was presented by the ECB to the chair and chief executives of the first-class counties and the MCC on 19 April 2018, and was unanimously supported by the board of the new competition.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] At first it was proposed that each innings would involve 15 six-ball overs and a final 10-ball over.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] In February 2019, the ECB announced tweaks to the proposed rules of 100-ball cricket.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] The competition will instead contain 10 ten-ball overs, i.e. a change of ends after ten balls.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] A bowler will be delivering five or 10 consecutive balls.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] A bowler would deliver a maximum of 20 balls per innings.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] Power-play conditions were also announced.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] Trial events using the format took place at The Purchasers annual cricket festival at Belmont House in Kent, and club level in England.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] In November 2018, the Warwickshire Cricket Board and Warwickshire County Cricket Club launched the 100-ball format club level tournament, which is designed to revitalise Sunday cricket at clubs across the Midlands.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] Called the Warwickshire Sunday Smash, the 16 team tournament is split into three divisions, with each side playing each team both home and away, throughout June and July.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] The teams include Solihull Blossomfield Cricket Club, Knowle & Dorridge, Sutton Coldfield, Bedworth, Alcester & Ragley, Stratford upon Avon, Water Orton, Four Oaks Saints, Moseley Ashfield and Aston Manor, who are all members of the Midlands Club Cricket Conference.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] The winners of each league and the best second place progressing to the Semi-Finals Day.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] The Finals Day took place on 1 September 2019 at Edgbaston.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] Stratford Upon Avon beat Knowle & Dorridge to win the first 100-ball competition in the UK.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] Shropshire County Cricket Club introduced the Swancote Energy Smash, which began in June 2019.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] It is a six-team tournament that has been divided into two groups, with games being played every Thursday night.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] The winners of each group is due to play in the inaugural final in early September 2019.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] The six teams are Shifnal, Claverley, Worfield, Bridgnorth, Chelmarsh and Wombourne.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] In May 2021 Shropshire Cricket league launched two 100-ball knock out competitions, known as the Aaron's 100 and Aaron's Premier 100, involving 53 teams from across Shropshire and mid-Wales.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] Cricket Wales launched the Cricket Wales U19’s 100 Ball Cup for under 19 year olds.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] It started on 25 June 2021 and is due to end with the final on 13 August 2021 at Ynystawe Cricket Club.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] The Cricket Paper National Girls U18 100 Ball Cup was established by Shrewsbury School.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] Originally known as the Shrewsbury School Girls U18 T20 in 2019, it is now a 100-ball cricket competition.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] The first professional competition using the 100-ball format was The Hundred in July 2021.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] The Hundred involves eight men's and women's teams across England and Wales.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] The first professional match using the new format involved the women's teams of the Oval Invincibles and Manchester Originals who played each other at The Oval in London on 21 July 2021.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] The Africa Cricket Association plans to hold an annual 100-ball competition to further boost the game within the continent.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] 100-ball cricket is a form of limited overs cricket, played by two teams each playing a single innings made up of 100 balls.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] English journalist George Dobell wrote in 2018 that proposals for the new format outlined by the ECB were nothing more than a further step towards "fast-food cricket", whereas others support the proposals.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] England's then Test captain, Joe Root, welcomed the ECB's plans for its new-team format in 2020.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] According to Root, it will attract a completely new audience.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] ODI and T20 captain, Eoin Morgan, had a similar opinion about this format.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] Former T20 captain Stuart Broad said he was hugely optimistic about the new format.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] Michael Vaughan also echoed Broad and stated that it will be a more appealing concept to broadcasters.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] Michael Atherton shared that a T20 match was originally to be completed in a 3-hour window and this can be achieved with the proposed format.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] New Zealand all-rounder Jimmy Neesham was bemused on this move, asking why the England and Wales Cricket Board is trying something different when the current format is already so successful.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] Current limited overs specialists Dawid Malan and Mark Wood shared that in spite of the new format, T20s will still remain as the preference.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] Former MCC chief Keith Bradshaw called the 100-ball tournament an innovation for innovation's sake, reasoning that the main reason behind this thought process is that the ECB could not exploit the T20 boom.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] The England and Wales Professional Cricketers' Association shared that, overall, players were open to this new idea.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] Meanwhile, Cricket Australia has no plans to tinker with its existing Big Bash League.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/100-ball-cricket] It also shared a concern that the introduction of shorter formats is further ignoring Test cricket.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] 3x3 has been a basketball format long played in streets and gyms across the world, albeit in a less formal way.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Starting in the late 2000s, 3x3 game rules started to become standardized throughout the United States, most notably through the Gus Macker and Hoop It Up tournament series, which held large events across the country that included teams and players from all skill levels.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] In 1992, Adidas launched its now-discontinued streetball competition.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Since then, the number of 3x3 events and competitions has been steadily growing around the world.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] A Romanian organization, Sport Arena Streetball, began hosting 3x3 events in Bucharest as early as 2005, helping to grow the sport locally and regionally before formal FIBA rules were introduced.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] FIBA first test 3x3 at the 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau, followed by further test events in April 2008 in the Dominican Republic and October 2008 in Indonesia.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The international debut of 3x3 under FIBA rules occurred at the 2009 Asian Youth Games, where 19 teams competed in the boys' tournament and 16 teams competed in the girls' tournament, with all games held at Anglican High School in Tanah Merah, Singapore.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] 3x3 made its worldwide competitive debut at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics in Singapore, where 20 teams competed in both boys' and girls' categories, with games held at the Youth Space.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Since then, FIBA has regularly held world championships in both open and U18 categories.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Bucharest, later called the "Mecca of 3x3 basketball" by Sports Illustrated, hosted the first FIBA Europe 3x3 Championships in 2014, an event that helped establish organized 3x3 competition across Europe.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] In subsequent years, the city also hosted international 3x3 tournaments, attracting teams from outside Europe.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] FIBA developed 3x3 as a standalone discipline with its own format and regular international competitions.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made its Olympic debut at the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The 3x3 basketball variation has also been used in several tournaments, such as the Nike 3ON3 Tournament and Spokane Hoopfest, the largest 3x3 basketball tournament in the world, held annually in Spokane, Washington.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] FIBA releases from time-to-time a supplement to its official basketball rules specifically for 3x3.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The rules state that regular FIBA rules apply to all situations not specifically addressed in the FIBA 3x3 rules.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The current set, both in an abbreviated version and longer format, was published in August 2019.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The current rules depart from regular full-court basketball in the following ways.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Each team consists of three players and one substitute.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Each team must have three players on the court when the game begins.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The game is played on a half-court with one basket.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The American NBA & WNBA standard half-court distance is 15.24 m (50 ft) wide & 14.33 m (47 ft) long.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The ball is the size of a size 6 basketball (720 mm, 28.5 in) as used in the women's full-court game and its mass is that of the size 7 standard (620 g, 22 oz) used in the men's full-court game.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] A coin toss is held immediately before the game, and the winning team of the coin flip can choose to take possession of the ball at the start of the game, or take the first possession of a potential overtime period.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] In turn, this means that if the game goes into overtime, the first possession goes to the team that started the game on defense.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The game begins with the defensive team passing the ball to the offensive team to signify the start of the game.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] All offensive players must begin outside of the arc (the opposite side of the arc of the net), and the defensive team must begin inside of the arc.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Once the offensive team receives the ball, the clock starts.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] This exchange is also used to restart the game from any dead ball situation.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The game is a single period of a maximum 10 minutes and the winner is the first team to score 21 or the team with the higher score at the end of the 10 minutes; scoring 21 points immediately ends the game.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Every successful shot inside the arc, including free throws, is awarded one point, while every successful shot outside of the arc ("downtown") is awarded two points.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] After a made goal or free throw (except for technical or unsportsmanlike fouls and team fouls 10 or more; see below), play restarts with a player from the non-scoring team taking the ball directly under the basket and then dribbling or passing it to a point behind the arc.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The defense is not allowed to play for the ball inside the block/charge semi-circle under the basket.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] In any held-ball situation, the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The offensive team must attempt a shot for a goal within 12 seconds.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] An offensive player may also not dribble inside the arc with their back or side to the basket for more than 3 consecutive seconds.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] For either violation the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] There is a Trent Tucker Rule in which with up to 0.2 seconds left in regulation or on the shot clock, a high lob, or tip-in must be made.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] A tie in regulation time leads to an untimed overtime period, after a one-minute intermission.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Whichever team began the game as the defensive team, begins overtime as the offensive team.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The first team to score two points wins the game.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Note: if a game is tied at 20 at the end of regulation, a team scoring their 21st point in overtime does not end the game.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Substitutions can occur only in a dead-ball situation; a substitute can only enter from behind the end line opposite the basket, and the substitution becomes official once the player leaving the game has "tagged up" by making physical contact with the substitute.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Each team is allowed one 30 second time-out per game.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Each personal or technical foul counts as one team foul, while each unsportsmanlike or disqualifying foul counts as two team fouls.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Personal fouls during the act of shooting inside the arc are awarded one free throw, while fouls during the act of shooting behind the arc and the shot is unsuccessful are awarded two free throws.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Team fouls 7, 8 and 9 are awarded two free throws, and all team fouls thereafter are awarded two free throws and possession of the ball.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The "bonus" rule specifically supersedes the normal rule for fouls in the act of shooting.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The un-timed overtime period is considered extension of regulation for purpose of team fouls.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The first unsportsmanlike foul against a player results in two free throws.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] A second unsportsmanlike foul, or a disqualifying foul, results in two free throws and possession.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] A player who commits two unsportsmanlike fouls is disqualified.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] A team loses the game by default if all of its players are disqualified.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] All technical fouls result in one free throw, with possession going to the team that was entitled to possession at that time.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] If a foul is committed that results in the non-fouling team retaining possession, i.e. a technical or "unsportsmanlike" foul, the non-fouling team will receive the exchange outside of the arc.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Offensive fouls, if not technical, unsportsmanlike, or disqualifying, never result in free throws, regardless of the number of team fouls.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] In the case of a double foul, no free throws are awarded to either team, regardless of team foul count or whether the double fouls were unsportsmanlike.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] FIBA sees 3x3 as a major vehicle for promotion of the game of basketball throughout the world.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] FIBA Secretary General and IOC member Patrick Baumann explained: "The 3x3 concept has all the elements and skills required for basketball, it has inspired and will continue to inspire many great players in the future.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] At the same time, it is the easiest and one of the most-effective ways to bring youngsters to basketball, keep them and promote our game.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] FIBA is pursuing a strategy to implement 3x3.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] FIBA has developed a digital community that acts as a repository for all FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events worldwide and offers all players an individual world ranking based on the points earned by players at FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Any event around the world can become FIBA-endorsed by using FIBA's freeware, EventMaker, to organise the event.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] All FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events are classified within an established competition hierarchy, thus forming an official competition network.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The pinnacle of this competition network is the FIBA 3x3 World Tour, which includes a series of World Tour Masters and one Final.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] A team can qualify for a World Tour Masters by playing in any of the designated World Tour qualifiers.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The North American National Basketball Association (NBA) has also embraced 3x3.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Since 2016, the NBA has held a summer series of tournaments known as "Dew NBA 3X", where local amateur players from around the US compete in regional events for cash prizes and a finals berth.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The men's and women's NBA 3X champions then advance to the USA Basketball national 3x3 championship to potentially represent their country internationally.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] These tournaments also include live music performances, 3-point shooting contests for fans, an *NBA 2K* eSports competition, and appearances from current NBA players.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The qualification system for the FIBA 3x3 World Cups for men and women differs radically from the system used for FIBA full-court competitions.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] According to *The New York Times*, 3x3 has "an unusual qualifying system designed to grow the sport all year long as much as find the best teams for the World Cup." National team entries are based strictly on a country's official 3x3 ranking.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The ranking system for national teams also considers individual player rankings.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] For example, the US women's team qualified for the 2018 World Cup while the men's team did not, even though the men were ranked higher than the women on the cutoff date.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Participating in a FIBA-sanctioned 3x3 event can earn ranking points; according to a FIBA executive, "Andorra has heavy participation every weekend." The current concentration of ranking events in Europe makes it more difficult for non-European nations, especially the US, to qualify.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The aforementioned FIBA executive, when asked about the prospect of the 2020 Olympic debut of 3x3 potentially lacking any participation from the US, admitted that "a lot of teams want to beat the US.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] After the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics, FIBA established a regular World Cup that always includes men and women competing simultaneously in open, U23 and U18 categories.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] World Cups are played every year, except in years when there are Youth Olympic Games or Olympic Games.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] The COVID-19 pandemic caused the cancellation of the 2020 event.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] Classification to the World Cup is based on the 3x3 Federation Ranking, which ranks all National Federations based on the 3x3 Individual World Ranking points of their top 100 nationals in the respective category (i.e. men, women, U23 men, U23 women, U18 men, and U18 women).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball became a regular European Games contest since its introduction at the 2015 European Games in Baku, Azerbaijan.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made a debut in Olympic programme for the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, Japan, for both men and women.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball was included in 2022 Commonwealth Games in Birmingham, England.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/3x3-basketball] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, FIBA banned Russian teams and officials from participating in FIBA 3x3 Basketball competitions.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] The AFL held two official Australian Football League (AFL) pre-season AFLX competitions featuring senior AFL clubs and players, in 2018 and 2019, but these were unpopular with spectators and did not return in 2020.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] The variation continues to be promoted by the AFL Commission as a participation sport in development regions and areas, and particularly where full-sized cricket grounds are not available.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] Since the COVID-19 pandemic, AFLX has been merged with AFL 9s and retained only the X brand, co-branding AFL 9s as Junior X, Youth X and Senior X and aligning it with the more widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] The rules of the game differed from standard Australian rules football in some significant ways.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] The game was played on a rectangular soccer-sized pitch, allowing matches to be hosted by stadiums that usually lacked the suitable field dimensions for Australian rules football.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] AFLX was first trialled at Arden Street Oval in January 2017.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] Two months later, it was trialed at was first trialled on a soccer pitch at Lakeside Stadium in a match between the Port Melbourne Football Club and Coburg Football Club.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] AFLX pre-season competition was launched by AFL chief executive officer Gillon McLachlan at Docklands Stadium on 6 February 2018.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] McLachlan said that AFLX would help promote football internationally.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] The 2018 competition attracted more than 40,000 fans to tournaments in Adelaide, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] In Melbourne, TV ratings were reported as "modest" by AFL standards, with the three events drawing an average five-city metro audience of over 120,000 on Channel Seven's secondary channels.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] The AFL made several rule tweaks midway through the second season in attempt to make it higher scoring by inflating the scoring points for behinds from 1 to 2, goals from 6 to 12 and Super Goals from 10 to 20.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] Whitten Legends Game was also played under "EJX" (modified version of AFLX named after E J Whitten) at AAMI Park in Melbourne.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] It attracted just 6,000 spectators, the lowest in the series history.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] AFLX did not return as a senior AFL competition in 2020, as AFL had a greater focus on AFLW.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] Post the COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased the number of players to 9, effectively merging AFLX with AFL 9s and aligning with the widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] The reception to the two AFL pre-season competitions among fans and the media was mostly poor, with ABC Radio Grandstand journalist Richard Hinds being particularly savage in labelling it a "hollow, unappealing, pressure-free, atmosphere-deficient, oval-in-a-rectangle hole yawn-fest".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/aflx] Con Stavros of RMIT's school of Economics, Finance and Marketing, expressed doubts about the potential of AFLX to export Australian rules football but acknowledged that using rectangular playing fields instead of the standard cricket ones would make such expansion easier.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Although similar to paintball in concept and gameplay, airsoft pellets do not leave visible dye markings on their target and hits are not always apparent, though the pellets can sometimes leave small bruises or welts on exposed skin (and so protective gear is still recommended).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The game therefore relies heavily on an honor system in which players who have been hit are expected to call themselves out of play in keeping with honesty, fairness and sportsmanship.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The airsoft guns used are mostly magazine-fed, with some having manual/battery motor-powered spring-piston pump power plants similar to Nerf Blasters, or pneumatically powered by replaceable compressed gas (e.g. propane ("green gas"), 1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane or CO2) canisters.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Many airsoft guns also have mounting platforms compatible with genuine firearm accessories, and most cosmetically resemble real firearms.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] This makes them popular for military simulation and historical reenactments.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] There are also professional gun safety and weapon manipulation training conducted with airsoft in some fields, such as law enforcement training, due to better safety and lower cost.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The United States Coast Guard, for instance, officially adopted airsoft for training in 2018.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Airsoft gameplay varies in style and composition, but often ranges from action shooting to short organized live action role-playing (LARP) scenarios, close quarters battle skirmishes, military simulations (MilSim) or historical reenactments.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] It is played in indoor courses or outdoor fields.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Combat situations on the field may involve the use of genuine military tactics to achieve objectives set in each game.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Participants may attempt to emulate the tactical equipment and accessories used by modern military and police organizations.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] A game is normally kept safe by trained professionals acting as supervisors and marshals.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Before gameplay, an airsoft gun's muzzle velocity is usually checked through a chronograph and usually measured in feet per second (FPS) or joules, a measurement for kinetic energy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Some countries have a set velocity or muzzle energy restriction; guns shooting over the legal muzzle velocity can be confiscated.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Some playing fields further restrict minimum engagement distances, requiring players to yell "Bang Bang!" or other verbal phrases in order to prevent shooting other players at close distances, which may cause injury.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] In certain countries use of laser sights of any kind is illegal, including gun scopes with integrated lasers.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Airsoft originated in postwar Japan during the early 1970s, when photographer Ichiro Nagata, an avid shooting enthusiast himself, thought about making modelguns that shoot real projectiles that could not kill or wound.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Early airsoft guns use a manual spring-piston design and are essentially single-shot, tailoring to the needs of shooting enthusiasts while conforming to Japan's strict weapons control laws.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Originally designed for target shooting, the plastic balls used in these "guns" can be shot at humans without causing injury due to the low muzzle energy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] These new-generation replica guns were trademarked as **soft air guns** because the refrigerant propellant used was significantly weaker ("soft") than the canistered CO2 used in proper airguns (pellet guns and BB guns).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] This practical convenience of AEGs led soft air guns to quickly become popular for casual MilSim games, which the Japanese call **survival games** (サバイバルゲーム, *sabaibaru gēmu*).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Asahi Firearms was also a model company from Japan who operated in the 1980s and 90s and was one of the early pioneers of the airsoft hobby.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Airsoft guns spread to the United Kingdom in the late 1980s and early 1990s via a company called LS.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] They were sold in separate pieces and had to be assembled out-of-box before they were capable of shooting.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] These then became available to the rest of Europe and North America and rapidly gained popularity worldwide.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Since the mid-1980s, airsoft has been adapted with a purely recreational application in mind, and the sport is enjoyed by all ages.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Airsoft replicas are produced globally, with the majority being manufactured in East Asia.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Many law enforcement agencies and military units within the United States now start using airsoft for force-on-force tactical training drills.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The guns used in airsoft are typically classified as imitation firearms.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] They have a mechanism for shooting projectiles 6 mm, 6.4 mm, or 8 mm in diameter.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Some companies produce full replicas of counterpart grenade launchers which fire a projectile spray of 6 millimetres (0.24 in) pellets by use of a high-powered spring mechanism or a compressed gas propellant (i.e. green gas, propane, compressed air, or CO2).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] There is also a type of airsoft gun that is powered by a single (HPA) high-pressure air tank and a battery pack to power the internal FCU "Fire Control Unit" computer board.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] These guns are often known for their high and adjustable RPS or "Rounds Per Second" and durability.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] These HPA replicas are most often referred to as "PolarStars", although this refers to a popular brand of HPA engines and accessories.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] A typical airsoft gun is noticeably lighter than its "real steel" counterpart due to the use of aluminum alloy and plastic materials, though some have added weights in them for a more realistic feel.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Japan has specific rules about producing airsoft guns with metal parts, while newer guns, especially those made in Taiwan and Mainland China, have both internal and external parts that are metallic.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Smoke caps, as well as noise amplifiers, are available for certain airsoft guns to add realism.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Gas handgun magazines usually contain 10 to 30 pellets in a standard-capacity magazine; however, some are high-capacity magazines and can hold 50 rounds or more.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] In the case of AEG rifles, magazines come in either real-capacity (equivalent to the 30-round capacity of its real steel counterpart), low-capacity (10–50 rounds), mid-capacity (75–250 rounds), or high-capacity (250+ rounds).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] These magazines have spring followers like in BB guns.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The high-cap magazines often have a ratchet wheel that can be wound up periodically to force pellets up from the holding chamber of the magazine to the feeding chute.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Due to loose pellets in the reservoir, they often make a rattling noise when running or walking.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Some airsoft guns have a battery-powered box or drum magazine that holds thousands of pellets, but these are usually only used and allowed on LMGs (light machine gun) type replicas.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] It is common for owners to "tech" (modify) their guns.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The majority of gearboxes are made to Tokyo Marui specifications and have aftermarket upgrade parts available commercially.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Some gearboxes are proprietary in design.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] It is also possible to perform DIY modifications.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The "hop-up" system, which is installed in most stock airsoft rifles and pistols, is used to increase effective ranges by putting backspin on the pellets.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The Magnus effect causes the pellets to experience more lift as they are shot, counteracting against gravity.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] A small rubber nub protrudes into the top of the barrel through a small hole, applies pressure on a rubber bucking, and catches the top of the pellet as it moves past.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Adjusting the hop-up makes the nub more or less protrude into the bucking, so that backspin is increased or reduced.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Ideally, the hop-up should be adjusted so that the pellets fly as far as possible in a straight line without curving upward too far or dropping too quickly.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Hop-Up does decrease the muzzle velocity (a gun firing 340 ft/s (100 m/s) with the hop fully unwound can drop to as low as 300 ft/s (91 m/s)).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Ease and location of adjustment vary by gun design; some equipment provides a control that can be adjusted quickly during gameplay, while others may require partial disassembly.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] For example, a common location for Hop-Up adjustment is where the ejection port would be on a real firearm, which allows the machine to be covered while still allowing quick access to adjust the Hop-Up.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Some players customize their airsoft guns, either to improve performance or for purely aesthetic reasons.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Additions include scopes, fore-grips, and flashlights, red dot sights being the most commonly used.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Red dot sights are used to help aim, fore-grips are used to get a better grip on the airsoft gun, and flashlights (whether mounted or held in another hand) are used to illuminate dark areas and/or to blind opponents.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Even though in certain countries lasers are illegal, they are popular attachments in the U.S. and Europe.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Also available are "mock suppressors/silencers".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] These resemble the actual firearm accessory that dampens sound.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Since Airsoft does not use combustibles for propulsion these usually serve no function.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Although there are models that function to "light up" a glow-in-the-dark BB using UV light similar to a tracer round.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Most airsoft guns fire round plastic pellets, usually white, but Tracers are common as well.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The pellets mostly range from 0.12 to 0.48 g.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] However, the most popular weights for AEGs (automatic electric guns) and GBB* (Gas Blow-Back guns) are 0.20 g to 0.32 g (whose muzzle velocity ranges from approximately 250 ft/s (76 m/s) to 400 ft/s (120 m/s)).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Heavier rounds (0.36–0.40 g) are typically used in long-range and sniper applications since they are more stable in flight and less easily deflected by wind.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The pellets, which are called BBs (ball bearings), are usually bought in bags or bottles of 2,000 to 5,000, but other sizes are available, such as a 250,000 round (65 kg) package of tournament grade BBs.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Biodegradable BBs are a fraction more expensive than non-bio counterparts, but many fields require them.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] BBs are typically 5.95mm ±0.01 mm in diameter.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Due to the low muzzle energy (less than 1.5 J or 1.1 ft⋅lb even for high-power models) and poor sectional density, the pain an airsoft pellet causes on skin impact is about the same as getting pinched.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] As a reference value, a standard 0.20 gram 6 mm pellet, which is the most common size and weight, traveling at 100 m/s (330 ft/s) has 1 J (0.74 ft⋅lb) of kinetic energy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Calculating the kinetic energy of an airsoft projectile is important for ensuring player safety.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] While a projectile’s ability to cause injury or penetrate a surface technically depends on energy density—that is, the kinetic energy divided by the impact area—this variable is nearly constant in airsoft, as most BBs have standardized diameters of 6 mm or 8 mm.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] As a result, the primary factor affecting the potential for injury or penetration is simply the kinetic energy of the BB.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Despite this, safety limits in airsoft are often expressed solely in FPS, which fails to account for variations in BB mass.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] where m is the mass in kilograms and v is the speed in meters per second.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Different regions vary in the velocity airsoft guns are allowed to shoot at.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] In the United States, velocity differs from the type of gameplay field.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Close Quarter Battle arenas typically regulate velocity on airsoft guns at around 110 m/s (350 ft/s).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] For outdoor fields, velocity is usually regulated by the type of gun.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] With a standard 0.20 grams (3.1 gr) pellet, fully automatic Airsoft Electric Guns (AEGs) are often set at less than 120 m/s (400 ft/s), semi-automatic DMR-style AEGs at 120–140 m/s (400–450 ft/s), and bolt-action (manually cocked spring-piston) sniper rifles at 140–150 m/s (450–500 ft/s).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The maximum effective range of field-legal airsoft guns is around 100 m (110 yd) with a highly upgraded sniper rifle replica.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Most airsoft guns used for field play will have an effective range of around 43–67 m (47–73 yd), depending on the intended gameplay role.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Most Airsoft guns are capable of shooting from 60 to 125 m/s (200 to 410 ft/s), although it is also possible to purchase upgraded internals that will enable the gun to shoot up to 170 m/s (550 ft/s) or higher.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] In California, a common limit for CQB is 110 m/s (350 ft/s).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] In Ireland, Italy and Japan the muzzle energy limit for airsoft guns is 1 joule no matter what the type of gameplay.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] In the UK, the law allows weapons locked to semi-automatic and bolt-action rifles to fire up to 2.5 joules (at muzzle velocity up to 158 m/s or 518 ft/s).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Any weapon "which is capable of discharging two or more missiles successively without repeated pressure on the trigger" is limited, by law, at 1.3 joules (velocity up to 114 m/s or 374 ft/s).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Northern Ireland has a maximum velocity of 100 m/s (330 ft/s) with 0.20 g pellets, without regard to the type of equipment.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] In Sweden, the legal limitations of airsoft guns caps the energy limit at 10 joules for manual guns, and 3 joules for semi- and fully automatic guns.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The ballistics of spring- or electrically powered airsoft guns differ from real firearms in that a longer barrel will not always result in better accuracy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The "sweet spot" for barrel length in a spring/electric powered airsoft gun is around 450 mm (18 in), beyond which added barrel length will not improve accuracy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] In any case, barrel quality, velocity consistency, and hopup quality/design are more important factors with regard to accuracy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Added barrel length will result in slightly increased velocity if the cylinder size and compression are appropriate for the barrel length.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] For example, a gun with a large cylinder and a long barrel will shoot slightly harder than a gun with a small cylinder and a short barrel (*ceteris paribus*).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] This rule will apply even for barrels longer than 500 mm (20 in), if there is enough cylinder volume and air compression to propel the pellet through the barrel.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] However, the resulting velocity increase will be hardly noticeable.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The only considerable advantage of using a longer inner barrel in an AEG or spring-powered gun is that it generally will make the gun quieter due to the weakened muzzle pop.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] In gas-powered guns, added barrel length (to an appropriate extent) can result in increased velocity and accuracy to a degree.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Tighter-bore barrels will increase velocity because there will be less space between the pellet and the barrel for the air to escape through.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Most stock airsoft guns have 6.03–6.05 mm (0.237–0.238 in) bore barrels, but best performance is usually seen with "tightbore" barrels, which are 6.01–6.05 mm (0.237–0.238 in) in diameter.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] However, the tighter the bore, the more likely the chance of a pellet jam, and subsequently, tightbores need to be cleaned and lubricated regularly.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] It is generally agreed upon that a high-quality 6.01-6.02 mm barrel will provide the highest muzzle velocity, while a good-quality 6.03 mm or 6.05 mm barrel will provide the best compromise between power, accuracy and ease of maintenance.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The actual accuracy difference between tightbore sizes is debatable and usually outweighed by bore consistency.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Although, with the newfound popularity with HPA guns, the debate has been opened that barrels with a larger diameter (up to 6.13 mm or 0.241 in) could provide a more accurate shot.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Due to the higher volume of air surrounding the pellet it negates the chance of the pellet coming into contact with the barrel, throwing the pellet's trajectory off, similar to a musket, in how the bullet slams about before leaving the barrel.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Airsoft guns are not to be confused with BB guns, which are airguns that shoot 4.5 mm (.177 in) metallic spherical pellets, unlike the plastic pellets shot by airsoft guns.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Many manufacturers and retailers suggest treating an airsoft gun like a real gun at all times.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] This will help alleviate safety issues resulting in an accidental/negligent discharge, or prevent a public panic due to a carelessly displayed airsoft gun being mistaken for a real firearm.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Most manufacturers include an orange tip on the muzzle of the airsoft gun for signaling and safety purposes, and most retailers urge consumers not to remove the orange tip as it is used to help distinguish them from a real firearm.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The orange tip serves many purposes, one of them being for law enforcement to help discern airsoft guns from real firearms and thus prevent unnecessary excessive forces.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The minimum safe level of gear required to participate in most games includes a pair of ANSI Z87.1 eye protection, preferably a fully sealed APEL-rated ballistic eyewear.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Traditional prescription glasses and sunglasses, or goggles not rated sufficiently for impact-resistance, may shatter and/or be perforated upon being struck when used for airsoft or paintball, causing injury to the eye.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Masks, face shields and other types of full-face coverings such as balaclavas are recommended at most airsoft fields.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Rules such as a maximum muzzle velocity and engagement distance guidelines are used by different groups.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Some organizations have created common safety rules and guidelines.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Most minimum engagement distances are 10 feet (3.0 m).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] When not actively playing, some fields require "barrel bags", also known as barrel socks, barrel condoms, barrel blockers, or barrel sleeves, to be placed over the muzzle of the gun.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The magazine is usually removed as well, and the gun fired to clear the chamber.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Most fields also require players to leave their guns set to the safety position when they are not shooting, a practice common when using real firearms.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] In certain countries, such as the Philippines, additional special rules have been adopted.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Airsoft is legal in most parts of the world.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Some countries have specific restrictions, such as maximum muzzle velocity and "unrealistic" coloring to distinguish them from actual firearms.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] They are legal throughout the United States, but restrictions do exist in cities like Chicago and Detroit.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The states of New Mexico, New York and New Jersey, however, do not allow airsoft guns to be used or handled publicly because of the resemblance to real firearms.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] They may be used on private property with the consent of the owner.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Customs and Border Protection FAQ page states that Airsoft guns are considered look-alike firearms which require the special blaze orange marking.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] In Ireland, Airsoft guns are classified as Realistic Imitation Firearms but not restricted as much as in the United Kingdom.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Under the Criminal Justice Act of 2006, Airsoft guns are legal in the Republic.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] One can buy, sell and import Airsoft guns without notifying relevant law enforcement authorities.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] They do not need to be painted in fluorescent colours, they do not need to have an orange tip, but they cannot launch the projectile with a kinetic energy exceeding 1 joule.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] However, carrying an imitation firearm in public is prohibited, and a gun carry case is required, as for real firearms.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Airsoft shops are spread over the country, and buyers must be aged 18 or over to purchase an airsoft gun.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] There is no age limit on Airsoft, as long as a minor has an adult's permission.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] In the United Kingdom, most Airsoft guns are classified as realistic imitation firearms or RIFs.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The sale, manufacture, or importation (but not gifting) of these is illegal under the Violent Crime Reduction Act 2006.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] A defence is allowed for selling for specific purposes including airsoft skirmishing.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The minimum age for buying any imitation firearm in the UK is 18.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] It is an offence to possess an imitation firearm in a public place without a reasonable excuse, for example traveling to, or from, or being at an airsoft skirmish site.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Most UK airsoft sites and retailers participate in the United Kingdom Airsoft Retailer Association Ltd (UKARA) registration scheme.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] A player who has participated in at least 3 skirmishes over a period of at least 56 days at the same skirmish site can be registered by that site.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Retailers have access to the database to verify that the purchaser can provide them with a defence.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The Border Agency also has access to check legality of imports.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] As an alternative to RIFs, IFs (Imitation Firearms, including 'two tones') are available in the UK.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] These are RIFs which have been painted a bright colour (excluding white/silver/gold) over at least 51% of the item.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] No specific defence is required for selling an IF, although the minimum age for purchasing remains 18.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] In Canada, there are laws pertaining to airsoft importing.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] All airsoft guns that are bought in Canada are legal, but when importing it, the gun has to have between 366FPS and 500FPS to pass inspection at customs, otherwise the gun will be shipped back or destroyed.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Airsoft guns in the United States are sold with a federally mandated orange tip which must be 1/4 inch or longer covering the muzzle of the replica.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Airsoft technology is used in military training and law enforcement training.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Due to airsoft's realism, relatively safe projectiles, and economical ammunition, it is well-suited to war games and force-on-force scenarios to train and improve troop's tactical proficiency via associative learning and stress inoculation.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Multiple airsoft inventions were developed originally for military and law enforcement use.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Marking rounds were invented by Kerry T.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Bowden to allow trainees to see where each projectile landed.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Much like paintball and simunitions, these marking pellets would break upon impact, marking the target with luminescent liquid.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Unlike traditional plastic pellets, marking rounds are heavier to ensure breakage of the shell on impact.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The weight can be adjusted by adding heavier liquid.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Marking rounds are critical for trainees because they allow the shooter to see exactly where they hit the target.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] This allows them to extrapolate their mistakes and improve their aim.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Reusable grenades were improved by Scott Frank to emulate the fragmentation of a real grenade in war games and scenarios.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The grenade can be loaded with paint or pellets.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] It uses a quick release of highly pressurized gas to break the shell and quickly disperse pellets or paint in all directions.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Frank's grenade, although not the first, aimed to be as realistic and predictable as an actual grenade.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] He developed a more accurate timing mechanism and secondary safety mechanisms to prevent accidental discharge.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Both marking rounds and reusable grenades gave airsoft the edge it needed to enter into military and law enforcement training grounds.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The airsoft guns used for training differ from civilian models.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Guns manufactured for professional training are made to replicate the weight, feel and the sound of its real steel counterpart.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] In general, professional training airsoft guns are GBB models and enhanced with a weighted blowback mechanism to increase the force of the kick.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Some are AEGs and are built with a blowback mechanism.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] They are also outfitted with muzzle protectors that amplify the sound to a decibel level comparable to that of a real firearm.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] The average FPS for professional training airsoft guns is higher than civilian models.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Economically, airsoft is cheaper than simulation training.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Benjamin Kratz, Fort Jackson's battalion executive officer, said that one blank M16 round can cost as much as 32 airsoft rounds.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] Airsoft can also be used in military simulations such as in malls or prisons to add to the immersion.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/airsoft] There are different event producers like MiR Tactical holding these events.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The **American Civil War** (April 12, 1861 – May 26, 1865; also known by other names) was a civil war in the United States between the Union ("the North") and the Confederacy ("the South"), which was formed in 1861 by states that had seceded from the Union to preserve slavery in the United States.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The South saw slavery as threatened because of the election of Abraham Lincoln and the growing abolitionist movement in the North.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The war ended with Union victory, the dissolution of the Confederacy and the abolition of slavery, freeing four million African Americans.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Decades of controversy over slavery came to a head when Abraham Lincoln, a Republican who opposed slavery's expansion, won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Seven slave states in the South responded to Lincoln's victory by seceding from the United States and forming the Confederate States of America.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy seized US forts and other federal assets in the South.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The war began on April 12, 1861, when the Confederacy bombarded Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] A wave of enthusiasm for war swept over the North and South, as military recruitment soared.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Four more Southern states seceded after the war began and, led by its president, Jefferson Davis, the Confederacy comprised eleven states, containing a third of the US population.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Four years of intense combat, mostly in the South, ensued.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] During 1861–1862 in the western theater, the Union made permanent gains, though in the eastern theater the conflict was inconclusive.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The abolition of slavery became a Union war goal on January 1, 1863, when Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared all slaves in rebel states to be free, applying to more than 3.5 million of the 4 million enslaved people in the country.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] To the west, the Union first destroyed the Confederacy's river navy by the summer of 1862, then much of its western armies, and seized New Orleans.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The successful 1863 Union siege of Vicksburg split the Confederacy in two at the Mississippi River, while Confederate general Robert E.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Lee's incursion north failed at the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Grant's western successes led Lincoln to promote him to command of all Union armies in 1864.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Inflicting an ever-tightening naval blockade of Confederate ports, the Union marshaled resources and manpower to attack the Confederacy from all directions.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] This led to the fall of Atlanta in 1864 to Union general William Tecumseh Sherman, followed by his March to the Sea, which culminated in his taking Savannah.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The last significant battles raged around the ten-month Siege of Petersburg, gateway to the Confederate capital of Richmond.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates abandoned Richmond, and on April 9, 1865, Lee surrendered to Grant following the Battle of Appomattox Court House, setting in motion the end of the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln lived to see this victory but was shot by an assassin on April 14, dying the next day.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] By the end of the war, much of the South's infrastructure had been destroyed.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy collapsed, the Thirteenth Amendment abolished slavery, and four million enslaved black people were freed.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The war-torn nation then entered the Reconstruction era in an attempt to rebuild the country, bring the former Confederate states back into the United States, and grant civil rights to freed slaves.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The war is one of the most extensively studied and written about episodes in the history of the United States.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] It remains the subject of cultural and historiographical debate.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Of continuing interest is the myth of the Lost Cause of the Confederacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The war was among the first to use industrial warfare.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Railroads, the electrical telegraph, steamships, the ironclad warship, and mass-produced weapons were widely used.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The war left an estimated 700,000 soldiers dead, along with an undetermined number of civilian deaths, making it the deadliest in American history.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The technology and brutality of the Civil War foreshadowed the coming world wars.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The origins of the war were rooted in the desire of the Southern states to preserve the institution of slavery.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Historians in the 21st century overwhelmingly agree on the centrality of slavery in the conflict—at least for the Southern states.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] They disagree on the North's reasons for refusing to allow the Southern states to secede.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The pseudo-historical Lost Cause ideology denies that slavery was the principal cause of the secession, a view disproven by historical evidence, including the seceding states' own secession documents.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The principal political battle leading to Southern secession was over whether slavery would expand into the Western territories destined to become states.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Initially Congress had admitted new states into the Union in pairs, one slave and one free.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] This had kept a sectional balance in the Senate but not in the House of Representatives, as free states outstripped slave states in numbers of eligible voters.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Thus, at mid-19th century, the free-versus-slave status of the new territories was a critical issue, both for the North, where anti-slavery sentiment had grown, and for the South, where the fear of slavery's abolition had grown.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Another factor leading to secession and the formation of the Confederacy was the development of white Southern nationalism in the preceding decades.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The primary reason for the North to reject secession was to preserve the Union, a cause based on American nationalism.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Background factors in the run up to the Civil War were partisan politics, abolitionism, nullification versus secession, Southern and Northern nationalism, expansionism, economics, and modernization in the antebellum period.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Abraham Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Southern leaders feared Lincoln would stop slavery's expansion and put it on a course toward extinction.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] His victory triggered declarations of secession by seven slave states of the Deep South, all of whose riverfront or coastal economies were based on cotton that was cultivated by slave labor.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was not inaugurated until March 4, 1861, four months after his 1860 election, which afforded the South time to prepare for war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Nationalists in the North and "Unionists" in the South refused to accept the declarations of secession, and no foreign government ever recognized the Confederacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The US government, under President James Buchanan, refused to relinquish the nation's forts, which the Confederacy claimed were located in their territory.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] According to Lincoln, the American people had demonstrated, beginning with their victory in the American Revolution and Revolutionary War and subsequent establishment of a sovereign nation, that they could successfully establish and administer a republic.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Yet, Lincoln believed, a question remained unanswered: Could the nation be maintained as a republic, with its government selected by vote of the people, in the face of internal attempts to destroy it or separate from it?
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's election provoked South Carolina's legislature to call a state convention to consider secession.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] South Carolina had done more than any other state to advance the notion that a state had the right to nullify federal laws and even secede.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] On December 20, 1860, the convention unanimously voted to secede and adopted a secession declaration.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] It argued for states' rights for slave owners but complained about states' rights in the North in the form of resistance to the federal Fugitive Slave Act, claiming that Northern states were not fulfilling their obligations to assist in the return of fugitive slaves.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The "cotton states" of Mississippi, Florida, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas followed suit, seceding in January and February 1861.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Among the ordinances of secession, those of Texas, Alabama, and Virginia mentioned the plight of the "slaveholding states" at the hands of Northern abolitionists.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The rest made no mention of slavery but were brief announcements by the legislatures of the dissolution of ties to the Union.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] However, at least four—South Carolina, Mississippi, Georgia, and Texas—provided detailed reasons for their secession, all blaming the movement to abolish slavery and its influence over the North.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Southern states believed that the Fugitive Slave Clause made slaveholding a constitutional right.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] These states agreed to form a new federal government, the Confederate States of America, on February 4, 1861.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] They took control of federal forts and other properties within their boundaries, with little resistance from outgoing president James Buchanan, whose term ended on March 4.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Buchanan said the Dred Scott decision was proof the Southern states had no reason to secede and that the Union "was intended to be perpetual".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] He added, however, that "The power by force of arms to compel a State to remain in the Union" was not among the "enumerated powers granted to Congress".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] A quarter of the US army—the Texas garrison—was surrendered in February to state forces by its general, David E.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia left the rest of Virginia and joined the Union as West Virginia because of the slavery issue.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] As Southerners resigned their Senate and House seats, Republicans could pass projects that had been blocked.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] These included the Morrill Tariff, land grant colleges, a Homestead Act, a transcontinental railroad, the National Bank Act, authorization of United States Notes by the Legal Tender Act of 1862, the end of slavery in the District of Columbia, and a ban on slavery in the territories.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Revenue Act of 1861 introduced an income tax to help finance the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In December 1860, the Crittenden Compromise was proposed to re-establish the Missouri Compromise line, by constitutionally banning slavery in territories to the north of it, while permitting it to the south.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Compromise would likely have prevented secession, but Lincoln and the Republicans rejected it.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln stated that any compromise that would extend slavery would bring down the Union.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] A February peace conference met in Washington, proposing a solution similar to the Compromise; it was rejected by Congress.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Republicans proposed the Corwin Amendment, an alternative, not to interfere with slavery where it existed, but the South regarded it as insufficient.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The remaining eight slave states rejected pleas to join the Confederacy, following a no-vote in Virginia's First Secessionist Convention on April 4.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] On March 4, Lincoln was sworn in as president.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In his first inaugural address, he argued that the Constitution was a *more perfect union* than the earlier Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union, was a binding contract, and that secession was "legally void".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] He did not intend to invade Southern states, nor to end slavery where it existed, but he said he would use force to maintain possession of federal property, including forts, arsenals, mints, and customhouses that had been seized.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] "The mails, unless repelled, will continue to be furnished in all parts of the Union." Where conditions did not allow peaceful enforcement of federal law, US marshals and judges would be withdrawn.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] No mention was made of bullion lost from mints.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] He stated that it would be US policy "to collect the duties and imposts"; "there will be no invasion, no using of force against or among the people anywhere" that would justify an armed revolution.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] His speech closed with a plea for restoration of the bonds of union, famously calling on "the mystic chords of memory" binding the two regions.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy sent delegates to Washington to negotiate a peace treaty.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln rejected negotiations, because he claimed that the Confederacy was not a legitimate government and to make a treaty with it would recognize it as such.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln instead attempted to negotiate directly with the governors of seceded states, whose administrations he continued to recognize.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Complicating Lincoln's attempts to defuse the crisis was Secretary of State William H.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Seward, who had been Lincoln's rival for the Republican nomination.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Embittered by his defeat, Seward agreed to support Lincoln's candidacy only after he was guaranteed the executive office then considered the second most powerful.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In the early stages of Lincoln's presidency Seward held little regard for him, due to his perceived inexperience.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Seward viewed himself as the de facto head of government, the "prime minister" behind the throne.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Seward attempted to engage in unauthorized and indirect negotiations that failed.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was determined to hold all remaining Union-occupied forts in the seceded states: Fort Pickens, Fort Jefferson, and Fort Taylor in Florida, and Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The American Civil War began on April 12, 1861, when Confederate forces opened fire on the Union-held Fort Sumter.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter is located in the harbor of Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Its status had been contentious for months.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Outgoing president Buchanan had dithered in reinforcing its garrison, commanded by Major Robert Anderson.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson took matters into his own hands and on December 26, 1860, under the cover of darkness, sailed the garrison from the poorly placed Fort Moultrie to the stalwart island Fort Sumter.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson's actions catapulted him to hero status in the North.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] An attempt to resupply the fort on January 9, 1861, failed and nearly started the war then, but an informal truce held.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] On March 5, Lincoln was informed the fort was low on supplies.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter proved a key challenge to Lincoln's administration.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Back-channel dealing by Seward with the Confederates undermined Lincoln's decision-making; Seward wanted to pull out.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] But a firm hand by Lincoln tamed Seward, who was a staunch Lincoln ally thereafter.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln decided holding the fort, which would require reinforcing it, was the only workable option.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] On April 6, Lincoln informed the Governor of South Carolina that a ship with food but no ammunition would attempt to supply the fort.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] James McPherson describes this win-win approach as "the first sign of the mastery that would mark Lincoln's presidency"; the Union would win if it could resupply and hold the fort, and the South would be the aggressor if it opened fire on an unarmed ship supplying starving men.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] An April 9 Confederate cabinet meeting resulted in Davis ordering General P.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Beauregard to take the fort before supplies reached it.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] At 4:30 a.m. on April 12, Confederate forces fired the first of 4,000 shells at the fort; it fell the next day.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The loss of Fort Sumter lit a patriotic fire under the North.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] On April 15, Lincoln called on the states to field 75,000 militiamen for 90 days; impassioned Union states met the quotas quickly.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] On May 3, 1861, Lincoln called for an additional 42,000 volunteers for three years.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Shortly after this, Virginia, Tennessee, Arkansas, and North Carolina seceded and joined the Confederacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] To reward Virginia, the Confederate capital was moved to Richmond.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland, Delaware, Missouri, and Kentucky, known as the border states, were slave states that had not seceded and whose people had divided loyalties to the North and South, with some men enlisting in the Union Army and others in the Confederate Army.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia may be compared to the border states because it had slavery after it separated from Virginia and was admitted to the Union on June 20, 1863, but it was admitted under a plan of gradual emancipation known as the Willey Amendment.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's territory surrounded Washington, D.C., and could cut it off from the North.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] It had anti-Lincoln officials who tolerated anti-army rioting in Baltimore and the burning of bridges, both aimed at hindering the passage of troops to Washington, D.C., and the South.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's legislature voted overwhelmingly to stay in the Union, but rejected hostilities with its southern neighbors, voting to close Maryland's rail lines to prevent their use for war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln responded by establishing martial law and suspending habeas corpus in Maryland, along with sending in militia units.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In *Ex parte Merryman*, Chief Justice Roger Taney found that only Congress could suspend habeas corpus, but Lincoln ignored his ruling.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln took control of Maryland and the District of Columbia by seizing prominent figures, including arresting one-third of the members of the Maryland General Assembly, who were pro-Confederate, on September 17, 1861, the day it intended to reconvene.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] All were held without trial at Fort McHenry in Baltimore.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In September 1861, federal troops imprisoned a Baltimore newspaper editor, Frank Key Howard, after he criticized Lincoln in an editorial for ignoring Chief Justice Taney's ruling in *Ex parte Merryman*.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Howard wrote a book about his prison experiences, which was published early in 1863.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] It "stressed the crowded conditions and spartan hardships of prison life ... [and] likened the conditions in Fort Lafayette to those on 'a slave-ship, on the middle passage'".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In Missouri, an elected convention on secession voted to remain in the Union.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] When pro-Confederate Governor Claiborne Fox Jackson called out the state militia, it was attacked by federal forces under General Nathaniel Lyon, who chased the governor and rest of the State Guard to the southwestern corner of Missouri (see Missouri secession).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Early in the war the Confederacy controlled southern Missouri through the Confederate government of Missouri but was driven out after 1862.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In the resulting vacuum, the convention on secession reconvened and took power as the Unionist provisional government of Missouri.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Kentucky did not secede but declared itself neutral.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] When Confederate forces entered in September 1861, its neutrality ended and the state reaffirmed its Union status while maintaining slavery.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Its jurisdiction extended only as far as Confederate battle lines in the Commonwealth, which at its greatest extent was over half the state, and it went into exile after October 1862.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] After Virginia's secession, a Unionist government in Wheeling asked 48 counties to vote on an ordinance to create a new state in October 1861.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] A voter turnout of 34 percent approved the statehood bill (96 percent approving).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Twenty-four secessionist counties were included in the new state, and the ensuing guerrilla war engaged about 40,000 federal troops for much of the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Congress admitted West Virginia to the Union on June 20, 1863.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginians provided about 20,000 soldiers to each side in the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] A Unionist secession attempt occurred in East Tennessee but was suppressed by the Confederacy, which arrested over 3,000 men suspected of loyalty to the Union; they were held without trial.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War was marked by intense and frequent battles.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Over four years, 237 named battles were fought, along with many smaller actions, often characterized by their bitter intensity and high casualties.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Historian John Keegan described it as "one of the most ferocious wars ever fought", where in many cases the only target was the enemy's soldiers.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] As the Confederate states organized, the US Army numbered 16,000, while Northern governors began mobilizing their militias.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate Congress authorized up to 100,000 troops in February.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] By May, Jefferson Davis was pushing for another 100,000 soldiers for one year or the duration, and the US Congress responded in kind.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In the first year of the war, both sides had more volunteers than they could effectively train and equip.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] After the initial enthusiasm faded, relying on young men who came of age each year was not enough.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Both sides enacted draft laws (conscription) to encourage or force volunteering, though relatively few were drafted.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy passed a draft law in April 1862 for men aged 18 to 35, with exemptions for overseers, government officials, and clergymen.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The US Congress followed in July, authorizing a militia draft within states that could not meet their quota with volunteers.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] European immigrants joined the Union Army in large numbers, including 177,000 born in Germany and 144,000 in Ireland.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] About 50,000 Canadians served, around 2,500 of whom were black.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] When the Emancipation Proclamation went into effect in January 1863, ex-slaves were energetically recruited to meet state quotas.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] States and local communities offered higher cash bonuses for white volunteers.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Congress tightened the draft law in March 1863.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Men selected in the draft could provide substitutes or, until mid-1864, pay commutation money.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Many eligibles pooled their money to cover the cost of anyone drafted.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Families used the substitute provision to select which man should go into the army and which should stay home.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] There was much evasion and resistance to the draft, especially in Catholic areas.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The New York City draft riots in July 1863 involved Irish immigrants who had been signed up as citizens to swell the vote of the city's Democratic political machine, not realizing it made them liable for the draft.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Of the 168,649 men procured for the Union through the draft, 117,986 were substitutes, leaving only 50,663 who were conscripted.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In the North and South, draft laws were highly unpopular.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, some 120,000 men evaded conscription, many fleeing to Canada, and another 280,000 soldiers deserted during the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] At least 100,000 Southerners deserted, about 10 percent of the total.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Southern desertion was high because many soldiers were more concerned about the fate of their local area than the Southern cause.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, "bounty jumpers" enlisted to collect the generous bonus, deserted, then re-enlisted under a different name for a second bonus; 141 were caught and executed.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] From a tiny frontier force in 1860, the Union and Confederate armies grew into the "largest and most efficient armies in the world" within a few years.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Some European observers at the time dismissed them as amateur and unprofessional, but historian John Keegan concluded that each outmatched the French, Prussian, and Russian armies, and without the Atlantic, could have threatened any of them with defeat.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Unionism was strong in certain areas within the Confederacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] As many as 100,000 men living in states under Confederate control served in the Union Army or pro-Union guerrilla groups.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Although they came from all classes, most Southern Unionists differed socially, culturally, and economically from their region's dominant prewar, slave-owning planter class.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] At the beginning of the Civil War, a parole system operated, under which captives agreed not to fight until exchanged.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] They were held in camps run by their army, paid, but not allowed to perform any military duties.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The system of exchanges collapsed in 1863 when the Confederacy refused to exchange black prisoners.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] After that, approximately 56,000 of the 409,000 POWs died in prisons, accounting for 10 percent of the conflict's fatalities.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Leonard writes that between 500 and 1,000 women enlisted as soldiers on both sides, disguised as men.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Women also served as spies, resistance activists, nurses, and hospital personnel.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Women served on the Union hospital ship *Red Rover* and nursed Union and Confederate troops at field hospitals.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Mary Edwards Walker, the only woman ever to receive the Medal of Honor, served in the Union Army and was given the medal for treating the wounded during the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] One woman, Jennie Hodgers, fought for the Union under the name Albert D.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] After she returned to civilian life, she continued to live as a man until she died in 1915 at the age of 71.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] During the war, women in the North advocated for social reforms and created ladies' aid societies, also called soldiers' aid societies, which provided supplies to soldiers on the battlefield and cared for sick and wounded soldiers.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Women in the North also held military rallies, village parades, and charity bazaars.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Anthony saw that supporting the war effort was a way to pave the future for women's suffrage movements.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In her appeal to Northern women's loyalty, Anthony challenged the inconsistencies of the nation's founding ideal and its actual practices concerning equality among women.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women during the Civil War also made great strides in the workforce, as they helped contribute to the war effort by stepping into roles that were traditionally held by men.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] While women rarely worked in factories before the war, many filled men's places as they felt they could erase some of the boundaries that separated them from male preserves of power.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Women were important in the workforce as they prepared and packed provisions, sewed uniforms and havelocks, and knitted socks and mittens.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] By entering these new environments, women made significant progress in the fight for women's equality in the workforce.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women were also essential in the wartime support, as they were active participants in the war narrative.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] While women were not allowed to fight on the battlefield in the Civil War, they exhibited a patriotism that gave them the strength to maintain courage for themselves as well as their households.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] While their men were off at war, Northern women created a landscape that emphasized love, sacrifice, and the nurturing of men's courage.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] This is demonstrated in feminized war literature that encouraged, expressed, and valorized men's patriotism.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Women's unwavering encouragement and affection towards fighting men became a cornerstone of the war effort as it helped sustain the spirits of the men on the frontlines.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate women during the Civil War focused on preserving the central economic institution of the Old South: the plantation.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] With so many men away at war, women were left with the land and the slaves.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] While some women hired male overseers to assist them in directing and maintaining newly female-headed plantations, other women decided to stay at the plantations and run the plantations themselves.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women became focused on keeping the economic structure of the South as they dealt with increasingly rebellious slaves.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The South relied on enslaved labor because it was an agrarian economy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] A good number of enslaved men labored for the Confederate army during the war, which meant that enslaved women and children were increasingly at the center of the work force on the plantations.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] White Southern women struggled to maintain morale on the home front as they dealt with problems without men.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Although Southern women were devoted to the Confederacy, many requested that their sons and husbands be discharged from the military to help them at home.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Eliza Adams wrote to the Confederate government to appeal for exemptions for her sons' military service, as she had sent five sons and also sons-in-laws to fight for the Confederacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women were torn between their patriotic ideals and their daily realities of life on the home front.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Union navy in 1861 was relatively small but, by 1865, expanded rapidly to 6,000 officers, 45,000 sailors, and 671 vessels totaling 510,396 tons.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Its mission was to blockade Confederate ports, control the river system, defend against Confederate raiders on the high seas, and be ready for a possible war with the British Royal Navy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The main riverine war was fought in the West, where major rivers gave access to the Confederate heartland.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The US Navy eventually controlled the Red, Tennessee, Cumberland, Mississippi, and Ohio rivers.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In the East, the Navy shelled Confederate forts and supported coastal army operations.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War occurred during the early stages of the industrial revolution, leading to naval innovations, including the ironclad warship.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy, recognizing the need to counter the Union's naval superiority, built or converted over 130 vessels, including 26 ironclads.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Despite these efforts, Confederate ships were largely unsuccessful against Union ironclads.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Union navy used timberclads, tinclads, and armored gunboats.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy experimented with the submarine CSS *Hunley*, which proved unsuccessful, and with the ironclad CSS *Virginia*, rebuilt from the sunken Union ship *Merrimack*.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] On March 8, 1862, *Virginia* inflicted significant damage on the Union's wooden fleet, but the next day, the first Union ironclad, USS *Monitor*, arrived to challenge it in the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The resulting three-hour Battle of Hampton Roads was a draw, proving ironclads were effective warships.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy scuttled the *Virginia* to prevent its capture, while the Union built many copies of the *Monitor*.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy's efforts to obtain warships from Great Britain failed, as Britain had no interest in selling warships to a nation at war with a stronger enemy and feared souring relations with the US.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] By early 1861, General Winfield Scott had devised the Anaconda Plan to win the war with minimal bloodshed, calling for a blockade of the Confederacy to suffocate the South into surrender.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln adopted parts of the plan but opted for a more active war strategy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In April 1861, Lincoln announced a blockade of all Southern ports; commercial ships could not get insurance, ending regular traffic.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The South blundered by embargoing cotton exports before the blockade was fully effective; by the time they reversed this decision, it was too late.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] "King Cotton" was dead, as the South could export less than 10% of its cotton.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade shut down the ten Confederate seaports with railheads that moved almost all the cotton.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] By June 1861, warships were stationed off the principal Southern ports, and a year later nearly 300 ships were in service.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates began the war short on military supplies, which the agrarian South could not produce in adequate numbers.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Northern arms manufacturers were restricted by an embargo, ending existing and future contracts with the South.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy turned to foreign sources, connecting with financiers and companies like S.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Isaac, Campbell & Company and the London Armoury Company in Britain, becoming the Confederacy's main source of arms.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] To transport arms safely to the Confederacy, British investors built small, fast, steam-driven blockade runners that traded arms and supplies from Britain, through Bermuda, Cuba, and the Bahamas in exchange for high-priced cotton.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Many were lightweight and designed for speed, only carrying small amounts of cotton back to England.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] When the Union Navy seized a blockade runner, the ship and cargo were condemned as a prize of war and sold, with proceeds given to the Navy sailors; the captured crewmen, mostly British, were released.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Southern economy nearly collapsed during the war due to multiple factors, the most notable being severe food shortages, failing railroads, loss of control over key rivers, foraging by Northern armies, and the seizure of animals and crops by Confederate forces.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Historians agree the blockade was a major factor in ruining the Confederate economy; however, Wise argues blockade runners provided enough of a lifeline to allow Robert E.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Lee, a Confederate general, to continue fighting for additional months, as a result of supplies that included 400,000 rifles, lead, blankets, and boots that the Confederate economy could no longer supply.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate cotton crop became nearly useless, which cut off the Confederacy's primary income source.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Critical imports were scarce, and coastal trade also largely ended.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade's success was not measured by the few ships, which slipped through, but by the thousands that never tried.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] European merchant ships could not obtain insurance for their ships and transport, and were too slow to evade the blockade, leading them to cease docking in Confederate ports.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] To fight an offensive war, the Confederacy purchased arms in Britain and converted British-built ships into commerce raiders, which targeted United States Merchant Marine ships in the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy smuggled 600,000 arms, enabling it to continue fighting for two more years.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] As insurance rates soared, American-flagged ships largely ceased traveling in international waters, though some were reflagged with European flags, which allowed them to continue operating.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] After the conclusion of the Civil War, the US government demanded Britain reimburse it for the damage caused by blockade runners and raiders outfitted in British ports.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Britain paid the US$15 million in 1871, which covered costs associated with commerce raiding but nothing more.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Although the Confederacy hoped Britain and France would join them against the Union, this was never likely, so they sought to bring them in as mediators.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Union worked to block this and threatened war against any country that recognized the Confederacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In 1861, Southerners voluntarily embargoed cotton shipments, hoping to start an economic depression in Europe that would force Britain to enter the war, but this failed.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Worse, Europe turned to Egypt and India for cotton, which they found superior, hindering the South's postwar recovery.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Cotton diplomacy proved a failure, because Europe had a surplus of cotton, while the 1860–62 crop failures in Europe made the North's grain exports critically important.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] It also helped turn European opinion against the Confederacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] It was said that "King Corn was more powerful than King Cotton", as US grain increased from a quarter to almost half of British imports.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Meanwhile, the war created jobs for arms makers, ironworkers, and ships to transport weapons.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's administration initially struggled to appeal to European public opinion.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] At first, diplomats explained that the US was not committed to ending slavery and emphasized legal arguments about the unconstitutionality of secession.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate representatives, however, focused on their struggle for liberty, commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] European government leaders welcomed the fragmentation of the ascendant American Republic." However, a European public with liberal sensibilities remained, which the US sought to appeal to by building connections with the international press.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] By 1861, Union diplomats like Carl Schurz realized emphasizing the war against slavery was the Union's most effective moral asset in swaying European public opinion.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Seward was concerned an overly radical case for reunification would distress European merchants with cotton interests; even so, he supported a widespread campaign of public diplomacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] US minister to Britain Charles Francis Adams proved adept and convinced Britain not to challenge the Union blockade.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy purchased warships from commercial shipbuilders in Britain, with the most famous being the CSS *Alabama*, which caused considerable damage and led to serious postwar disputes.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] However, public opinion against slavery in Britain created a political liability for politicians, where the anti-slavery movement was powerful.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] War loomed in late 1861 between the US and Britain over the *Trent* Affair, which began when US Navy personnel boarded the British ship *Trent* and seized two Confederate diplomats.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] However, London and Washington smoothed this over after Lincoln released the two men.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Prince Albert left his deathbed to issue diplomatic instructions to Lord Lyons during the *Trent* Affair.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] His request was honored, and, as a result, the British response to the US was toned down, helping avert war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In 1862, the British government considered mediating between the Union and Confederacy, though such an offer would have risked war with the US.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] British prime minister Lord Palmerston reportedly read *Uncle Tom's Cabin* three times when deciding what his decision would be.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Union victory at the Battle of Antietam caused the British to delay this decision.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] The Emancipation Proclamation increased the political liability of supporting the Confederacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Realizing that Washington could not intervene in Mexico as long as the Confederacy controlled Texas, France invaded Mexico in 1861 and installed the Habsburg Austrian archduke Maximilian I as emperor.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Washington repeatedly protested France's violation of the Monroe Doctrine.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Despite sympathy for the Confederacy, France's seizure of Mexico deterred it from war with the Union.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate offers late in the war to end slavery in return for diplomatic recognition were not seriously considered by London or Paris.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] After 1863, the Polish revolt against Russia further distracted the European powers and ensured they remained neutral.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] Russia supported the Union, largely because it believed the US counterbalanced its geopolitical rival, the UK.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p01] In 1863, the Imperial Russian Navy's Baltic and Pacific fleets wintered in the American ports of New York and San Francisco, respectively.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Eastern theater refers to the military operations east of the Appalachian Mountains, including Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland, and Pennsylvania, the District of Columbia, and the coastal fortifications and seaports of North Carolina.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan took command of the Union Army of the Potomac on July 26, 1861, and the war began in earnest in 1862.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Ohio forces would advance through Kentucky into Tennessee.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Missouri Department would drive south along the Mississippi River.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The westernmost attack would originate from Kansas.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Confederate force in the Eastern theater was the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Army originated as the (Confederate) Army of the Potomac, which was organized on June 20, 1861, from all operational forces in Northern Virginia.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] On July 20 and 21, the Army of the Shenandoah and forces from the District of Harpers Ferry were added.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Units from the Army of the Northwest were merged into the Army of the Potomac between March 14 and May 17, 1862.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Potomac was renamed *Army of Northern Virginia* on March 14.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Peninsula was merged into it on April 12, 1862.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] When Virginia declared its secession in April 1861, Robert E.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lee chose to follow his home state, despite his desire for the country to remain intact and an offer of a senior Union command.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] In his four-volume biography of Lee published in 1934 and 1935, historian Douglas S.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Freeman wrote that the army received its final name from Lee when he issued orders assuming command on June 1, 1862.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] However, Freeman wrote, Lee corresponded with Brigadier General Joseph E.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston, his predecessor in army command, before that date and referred to Johnston's command as the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Part of the confusion results from the fact that Johnston commanded the Department of Northern Virginia as of October 22, 1861, and the name Army of Northern Virginia was seen as an informal consequence of its parent department's name.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Jefferson Davis and Johnston did not adopt the name, but the organization of units as of March 14 was clearly the same organization that Lee received on June 1, and is generally referred to as the Army of Northern Virginia, even if that is correct only in retrospect.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] On July 4 at Harper's Ferry, Colonel Thomas J.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson assigned Jeb Stuart command of all cavalry companies of the Army of the Shenandoah, and Jackson eventually commanded the Army of Northern Virginia's cavalry.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Called the "Philippi Races" because of its brevity, Philippi, Virginia (now Philippi, WV) was the scene of the first organized land action of the American Civil War, on June 3, 1861.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] In July 1861, in the first in a series of prominent battles in the war, Union Army troops commanded by Maj.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Irvin McDowell attacked Confederate forces, which were under the command of Beauregard near the national capital in Washington.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy repelled the attack in the First Battle of Bull Run.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of the battle, the Union appeared to hold the upper hand.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Union Army routed Confederate forces, then holding defensive positions, but Confederate reinforcements under Joseph E.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston arrived from the Shenandoah Valley by railroad, and the battle's course quickly changed.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] A brigade of Virginians, commanded by Thomas J.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson, then a relatively unknown brigadier general from Virginia Military Institute, stood its ground, leading to Jackson earning the nickname "Stonewall".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln urged the Union Army to commence offensive operations against Confederate forces, which led General George B.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan, in the spring of 1862, to attack Virginia by way of the peninsula between the York River and James River southeast of Richmond.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan's army reached the gates of Richmond in the Peninsula campaign.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Also in the spring of 1862, in Shenandoah Valley, Jackson led his Valley Campaign, during which he employed rapid and unpredictable movements on interior lines.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson's 17,000 troops marched 646 miles (1,040 km) in 48 days, during which they won minor battles as they engaged three Union armies, comprising 52,000 men, including those of Nathaniel P.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont, preventing them from reinforcing the Union offensive against Richmond.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The swiftness of Jackson's troops earned them the nickname foot cavalry.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston halted McClellan's advance at the Battle of Seven Pines, but he was wounded in the battle, and Robert E.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lee and his senior subordinates, James Longstreet and Stonewall Jackson, defeated McClellan in the Seven Days Battles, forcing McClellan's retreat.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] During the Northern Virginia Campaign, which included the Second Battle of Bull Run, Confederate forces registered another important military victory.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan resisted General-in-Chief Halleck's orders to send reinforcements to John Pope's Union Army of Virginia, which enabled Lee's Confederate forces to defeat twice the number of combined enemy troops.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Emboldened by Second Bull Run, Confederate forces launched their first invasion of the North in the Maryland Campaign during which Lee led 45,000 Army of Northern Virginia troops across the Potomac River into Maryland on September 5.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln then restored Pope's troops to McClellan, and McClellan and Lee clashed in the Battle of Antietam near Sharpsburg, Maryland, on September 17, 1862, which proved the bloodiest single day in both the Civil War and US military history.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan failed to respond in any measurable way to Lee's attempt to invade the North at Antietam, leading to his replacement by Maj.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Burnside led Union Army troops in the Battle of Fredericksburg, where they were defeated on December 13, 1862.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Over 12,000 Union soldiers were killed or wounded during futile attempts by Union troops to launch frontal assaults against Marye's Heights.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] After the battle, Burnside was replaced by Maj.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Hooker, too, proved unable to defeat Lee's army; despite having more than twice as many troops as Lee, Hooker's Chancellorsville Campaign proved ineffective, and he was soundly defeated in the Battle of Chancellorsville, which was fought between April 30 and May 6, 1863.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Chancellorsville is known as Lee's "perfect battle" because his risky decision to divide his army paid off.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] During the Battle of Chancellorsville, Stonewall Jackson was shot in his left arm and right hand by friendly fire, leading to the amputation of his arm, and he died of pneumonia.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The fiercest fighting of the battle—and the second bloodiest day of the Civil War—occurred on May 3 as Lee launched multiple attacks against the Union position at Chancellorsville.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] That same day, John Sedgwick advanced across the Rappahannock River, defeated the small Confederate force at Marye's Heights in the Second Battle of Fredericksburg, and then moved westward, but Confederate forces succeeded in delaying Union forces in the Battle of Salem Church.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] George Meade during Lee's second invasion of the North, in June.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] In the Battle of Gettysburg, which proved the war's bloodiest and one of its most strategically significant, Meade defeated Lee in a three-day battle between July 1 and 3, 1863.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Gettysburg caused over 50,000 Union and Confederate casualties, but also proved the war's turning point, altering the course of the war in the Union's favor.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Pickett's Charge, launched July 3, on the final day of the Battle of Gettysburg, is considered the high-water mark of the Confederacy, representing the collapse of any credible prospect that the Confederacy could prevail in the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] At Gettysburg, Lee's Army of Northern Virginia suffered 28,000 casualties versus Meade's 23,000, and Lee was repelled in a failed attempt to invade and occupy Union territory.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Western theater refers to military operations between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River, including Alabama, Georgia, Florida, Mississippi, North Carolina, Kentucky, South Carolina, Tennessee, and parts of Louisiana.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Union forces in this theater were the Army of the Tennessee and Army of the Cumberland, named for the two rivers, Tennessee River and Cumberland River.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] After Meade's inconclusive fall campaign, Lincoln turned to the Western theater for new leadership.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] At the same time, the Confederate stronghold of Vicksburg surrendered, giving the Union control of the Mississippi River, permanently isolating the western Confederacy, and producing the new leader Lincoln needed, Ulysses S.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of Tennessee, which served as the primary Confederate force in the Western theater, was formed on November 20, 1862, when General Braxton Bragg renamed the former Army of Mississippi.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] While Confederate forces had successes in the Eastern theater, they were defeated many times in the West.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's key strategist and tactician in the West was Ulysses S.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Grant, who led the Union to victories in battles at Fort Henry (February 6, 1862) and Fort Donelson (February 11 to 16, 1862), earning him the nickname of "Unconditional Surrender" Grant.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] With these victories, the Union gained control of the Tennessee and Cumberland Rivers.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Nathan Bedford Forrest rallied nearly 4,000 Confederate troops and led them to escape across the Cumberland River.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Nashville and central Tennessee fell to the Union, leading to attrition of local food supplies and livestock and a breakdown in social organization.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate general Leonidas Polk subsequently invaded Columbus, Kentucky, which ended Kentucky's policy of neutrality and turned it against the Confederacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Grant used river transport and Andrew Hull Foote's gunboats of the Western Flotilla, threatening the Confederacy's "Gibraltar of the West" in Columbus, Kentucky.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Although rebuffed at Belmont, Grant cut off Columbus.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces, lacking their gunboats, were forced to retreat and the Union took control of west Kentucky and opened Tennessee in March 1862.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Shiloh, in Shiloh, Tennessee, in April 1862, Confederate forces launched a surprise attack on Union forces, pushing them back to the Tennessee River as night fell.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Over that night, however, the Navy landed reinforcements, and Grant counterattacked.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Grant and the Union ultimately won a decisive victory in the first battle with a high number of casualties in what proved to be the first in a series of such battles.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces lost Albert Sidney Johnston, considered their finest general, before Lee emerged to assume command.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] One of the early Union objectives was to capture the Mississippi River, which would permit it to cut the Confederacy in half.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Mississippi was opened to Union traffic to the southern border of Tennessee after it took Island No.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] 10, New Madrid, Missouri, and then Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, the Union Navy captured New Orleans.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] "The key to the river was New Orleans, the South's largest port [and] greatest industrial center." US naval forces under Farragut ran past Confederate defenses south of New Orleans.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces abandoned the city, giving the Union a critical anchor in the deep South, which allowed Union forces to move up the Mississippi.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Memphis fell to Union forces on June 6, 1862, allowing it to serve as a key base for further Union advances south along the Mississippi.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] On the Mississippi River, the Union took every fortress city with the exception of Vicksburg, Mississippi.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] But Confederate control of Vicksburg was sufficient in preventing the Union from controlling the entire river.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Bragg's second invasion of Kentucky in the Confederate Heartland Offensive included initial successes, including Kirby Smith's triumph in the Battle of Richmond and the capture of the Kentucky capital of Frankfort, Kentucky, on September 3, 1862.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The campaign ended with a meaningless victory over Maj.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Don Carlos Buell at the Battle of Perryville, and Bragg was forced to end his attempt to invade and control Kentucky.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lacking logistical support and infantry recruits, Bragg was instead forced to retreat, and ended up being narrowly defeated by Maj.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] William Rosecrans in the Battle of Stones River in Tennessee in what proved to be the culmination of the Stones River Campaign.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] US naval forces assisted Grant in the long, complex Vicksburg Campaign, which resulted in Confederate forces surrendering in the Battle of Vicksburg in July 1863, which cemented Union control of the Mississippi River in one of the war's turning points.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The one clear Confederate victory in the West was the Battle of Chickamauga.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] After Rosecrans' successful Tullahoma Campaign, Bragg, reinforced by Lt.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] James Longstreet's Corps, defeated Rosecrans, despite the defensive stand of Maj.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Rosecrans retreated to Chattanooga, Tennessee, where Bragg was then besieged in the Chattanooga campaign.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Grant marched to the relief of Rosecrans, where he led the defeat of Bragg in the Third Battle of Chattanooga, eventually causing Longstreet to abandon his Knoxville Campaign and driving Confederate forces out of Tennessee and opening a route to Atlanta and the heart of the Confederacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Trans-Mississippi theater refers to military operations west of the Mississippi, encompassing most of Missouri, Arkansas, most of Louisiana, and the Indian Territory in present-day Oklahoma.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's command was the Trans-Mississippi Division, or the Military Division of West Mississippi.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The first major battle of the Trans-Mississippi theater was the Battle of Wilson's Creek (August 1861).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates were driven from Missouri early in the war as a result of the Battle of Pea Ridge.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Extensive guerrilla warfare characterized the trans-Mississippi region, as the Confederacy lacked the troops and logistics to support regular armies that could challenge Union control.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Roving Confederate bands such as Quantrill's Raiders terrorized the countryside, striking military installations and civilian settlements.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The "Sons of Liberty" and "Order of the American Knights" attacked pro-Union people, elected officeholders, and unarmed uniformed soldiers.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] These partisans could not be driven out of Missouri, until an entire regular Union infantry division was engaged.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] By 1864, these violent activities harmed the nationwide antiwar movement organizing against the re-election of Lincoln.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri not only stayed in the Union, but Lincoln took 70 percent of the vote to win re-election.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Small-scale military actions south and west of Missouri sought to control Indian Territory and New Mexico Territory for the Union.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Glorieta Pass was the decisive battle of the New Mexico Campaign.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Union repulsed Confederate incursions into New Mexico in 1862, and the exiled Arizona government withdrew into Texas.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] In the Indian Territory, civil war broke out within tribes.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] About 12,000 Indian warriors fought for the Confederacy but fewer for the Union.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The most prominent Cherokee was Brigadier General Stand Watie, the last Confederate general to surrender.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] After the fall of Vicksburg in July 1863, Jefferson Davis informed General Kirby Smith in Texas that he could expect no further help from east of the Mississippi.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Although he lacked resources to beat Union armies, he built up a formidable arsenal at Tyler, along with his own Kirby Smithdom economy, a virtual "independent fiefdom" in Texas, including railroad construction and international smuggling.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Union, in turn, did not directly engage him.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's 1864 Red River Campaign to take Shreveport, Louisiana, failed and Texas remained in Confederate hands throughout the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The lower seaboard theater refers to military and naval operations that occurred near the coastal areas of the Southeast as well as the southern part of the Mississippi.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Union naval activities were dictated by the Anaconda Plan.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] One of the earliest battles was fought in November 1861 at Port Royal Sound, south of Charleston.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Much of the war along the South Carolina coast concentrated on capturing Charleston.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] In attempting to capture Charleston, the Union military tried two approaches: by land over James or Morris Islands or through the harbor.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Confederates were able to drive back each attack.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] A famous land attack was the Second Battle of Fort Wagner, in which the 54th Massachusetts Infantry took part.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Union suffered a serious defeat, losing 1,515 soldiers while the Confederates lost only 174.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] However, the 54th was hailed for its valor, which encouraged the general acceptance of the recruitment of African American soldiers into the Union Army, which reinforced the Union's numerical advantage.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Fort Pulaski on the Georgia coast was an early target for the Union navy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Following the capture of Port Royal, an expedition was organized with engineer troops under the command of Captain Quincy Adams Gillmore, forcing a Confederate surrender.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army occupied the fort for the rest of the war after repairing it.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, a Union naval task force commanded by Commander David Dixon Porter attacked Forts Jackson and St.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Philip, which guarded the river approach to New Orleans from the south.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] While part of the fleet bombarded the forts, other vessels forced a break in the obstructions in the river and enabled the rest of the fleet to steam upriver to the city.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Benjamin Butler landed near the forts and forced their surrender.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Butler's controversial command of New Orleans earned him the nickname "Beast".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The following year, the Union Army of the Gulf commanded by Maj.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Banks laid siege to Port Hudson for nearly eight weeks, the longest siege in US military history.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates attempted to defend with the Bayou Teche Campaign but surrendered after Vicksburg.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] These surrenders gave the Union control over the Mississippi.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Several skirmishes but no major battles were fought in Florida.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The biggest was the Battle of Olustee in early 1864.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Pacific coast theater refers to military operations on the Pacific Ocean and in the states and territories west of the Continental Divide.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of 1864, Lincoln made Grant commander of all Union armies.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Grant made his headquarters with the Army of the Potomac and put Maj.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] William Tecumseh Sherman in command of most of the western armies.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Grant understood the concept of total war and believed, along with Lincoln and Sherman, that only the utter defeat of Confederate forces and their economic base would end the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] This was total war not in killing civilians, but in injuring the Confederacy's capacity to produce and transport the supplies needed to continue the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman, at Grant's direction, seized provisions and destroyed homes, farms, and railroads, which Grant said "would otherwise have gone to the support of secession and rebellion.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Grant devised a coordinated strategy that would strike at the entire Confederacy from multiple directions.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Generals Meade and Benjamin Butler were ordered to move against Lee near Richmond, General Franz Sigel was to attack the Shenandoah Valley, General Sherman was to capture Atlanta and march to the Atlantic Ocean, Generals George Crook and William W.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Averell were to operate against railroad supply lines in West Virginia, and Maj.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Grant's army set out on the Overland Campaign intending to draw Lee into a defense of Richmond, where they would attempt to pin down and destroy the Confederate army.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army first attempted to maneuver past Lee and fought several battles, notably at the Wilderness, Spotsylvania, and Cold Harbor.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] These resulted in heavy losses on both sides and forced Lee's Confederates to fall back repeatedly.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Yellow Tavern, the Confederates lost Jeb Stuart.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] An attempt to outflank Lee from the south failed under Butler, who was trapped inside the Bermuda Hundred river bend.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Each battle resulted in setbacks for the Union that mirrored those they had suffered under prior generals, though unlike them, Grant chose to fight on rather than retreat.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Grant was tenacious and kept pressing Lee's Army of Northern Virginia back to Richmond.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] While Lee was preparing for an attack on Richmond, Grant unexpectedly turned south to cross the James River and began the protracted Siege of Petersburg, where the two armies engaged in trench warfare for over nine months.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] To deny the Confederacy continued use of the Shenandoah Valley as a base from which to launch invasions of Maryland and the Washington area, and to threaten Lee's supply lines for his forces, Grant launched the Valley campaigns in May 1864.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Sigel were repelled at the Battle of New Market by Confederate Gen.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of New Market was the Confederacy's last major victory, and included a charge by teenage VMI cadets.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] After relieving Sigel, and following mixed performances by his successor, Grant finally found a commander, General Philip Sheridan, aggressive enough to prevail against the army of Maj.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] After a cautious start, Sheridan defeated Early in a series of battles in September and October 1864, including a decisive defeat at the Battle of Cedar Creek.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Sheridan then proceeded through that winter to destroy the agricultural base of the Shenandoah Valley, a strategy similar to the tactics Sherman later employed in Georgia.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Sherman maneuvered from Chattanooga to Atlanta, defeating Confederate Generals Joseph E.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The fall of Atlanta on September 2, 1864, guaranteed the reelection of Lincoln.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Hood left the Atlanta area to swing around and menace Sherman's supply lines and invade Tennessee in the Franklin–Nashville Campaign.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] John Schofield defeated Hood at the Battle of Franklin, and George H.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Thomas dealt Hood a massive defeat at the Battle of Nashville, effectively destroying Hood's army.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Leaving Atlanta, and his base of supplies, Sherman's army marched, with no destination set, laying waste to about 20 percent of the farms in Georgia on his March to the Sea.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] He reached the Atlantic at Savannah, Georgia, in December 1864.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman's army was followed by thousands of freed slaves; there were no major battles along the march.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman turned north through South Carolina and North Carolina in his Carolinas campaign, to approach the Confederate Virginia lines from the south, increasing the pressure on Lee's army.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lee's army, thinned by desertion and casualties, was now much smaller than Grant's.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] One last Confederate attempt to break the Union hold on Petersburg failed at the decisive Battle of Five Forks on April 1.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Union now controlled the entire perimeter surrounding Richmond–Petersburg, completely cutting it off from the Confederacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Realizing the capital was now lost, Lee's army and the Confederate government were forced to evacuate.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate capital fell on April 2–3, to the Union XXV Corps, composed of black troops.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The remaining Confederate units fled west after a defeat at Sayler's Creek on April 6.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] front page celebrated Lee's surrender, headlining how Grant let Confederate officers retain their sidearms and "paroled" the Confederate officers and men.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] News of Lee's April 9 surrender reached this southern newspaper (Savannah, Georgia) on April 15—after the April 14 shooting of President Lincoln.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The article quotes Grant's terms of surrender.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lee did not intend to surrender, but planned to regroup at Appomattox Station, where supplies were to be waiting, and then continue the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Grant chased Lee and got in front of him, so that when Lee's army reached the village of Appomattox Court House, they were surrounded.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] After an initial battle, Lee decided the fight was hopeless, and surrendered his Army of Northern Virginia to Grant on April 9, 1865, during a conference at the McLean House.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] In an untraditional gesture and as a sign of Grant's respect and anticipation of peacefully restoring Confederate states to the Union, Lee was permitted to keep his sword and horse, Traveller.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] His men were paroled, and a chain of Confederate surrenders began.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] On April 14, 1865, Lincoln was shot by John Wilkes Booth, a Confederate sympathizer.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's vice president, Andrew Johnson, was unharmed, because his would-be assassin, George Atzerodt, lost his nerve, so Johnson was immediately sworn in as president.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Confederate forces across the South surrendered, as news of Lee's surrender reached them.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] On April 26, the same day Sergeant Boston Corbett killed Booth at a tobacco barn, Johnston surrendered nearly 90,000 troops of the Army of Tennessee to Sherman at Bennett Place, near present-day Durham, North Carolina.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] It proved to be the largest surrender of Confederate forces.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] On May 4, all remaining Confederate forces in Alabama, Mississippi, and Louisiana east of the Mississippi, under the command of Lt.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate president Davis was captured in retreat at Irwinville, Georgia on May 10.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The final land battle was fought on May 13, 1865, at the Battle of Palmito Ranch in Texas.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Buckner, acting for Edmund Smith, signed a military convention surrendering Confederate forces in the Trans-Mississippi Department.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] This date is often cited by contemporaries and historians as the effective end date of the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] On June 2, with most of his troops having already gone home, a reluctant Kirby Smith had little choice but to sign the official surrender document.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] General Stand Watie became the last Confederate general to surrender his forces.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Gordon Granger announced General Order No.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] 3, bringing the Emancipation Proclamation into effect in Texas and freeing the last slaves of the Confederacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The anniversary of this date is now celebrated as Juneteenth.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The naval part of the war ended more slowly.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Britain finally responded on June 6, by transmitting a letter from Foreign Secretary John Russell, 1st Earl Russell, to the Lords of the Admiralty withdrawing rights to Confederate warships to enter British ports and waters.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] US Secretary of State Seward welcomed the withdrawal of concessions to the Confederates.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Finally, on October 18, Russell advised the Admiralty that the time specified in his June message had elapsed and "all measures of a restrictive nature on vessels of war of the United States in British ports, harbors, and waters, are now to be considered as at an end".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Nonetheless, the final Confederate surrender was in Liverpool, England where James Iredell Waddell, the captain of CSS *Shenandoah*, surrendered the cruiser to British authorities on November 6.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Legally, the war did not end until August 20, 1866, when President Johnson issued a proclamation that declared "that the said insurrection is at an end and that peace, order, tranquillity, and civil authority now exist in and throughout the whole of the United States of America".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The causes of the war, reasons for its outcome, and even its name are subjects of lingering contention.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The North and West grew wealthy while the once-rich South became poor for a century.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The national political power of the slaveowners and rich Southerners ended.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Historians are less sure about the results of postwar Reconstruction, especially regarding the second-class citizenship of the freedmen and their poverty.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Historians have debated whether the Confederacy could have won the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, argue Confederate victory was possible.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson argues that the North's advantage in population and resources made Northern victory likely, but not guaranteed.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] He argues that if the Confederacy had fought using unconventional tactics, it would have more easily been able to hold out long enough to exhaust the Union.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Confederates did not need to invade and hold enemy territory to win, but only to fight a defensive war to convince the North the cost of winning was too high.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The North needed to conquer and hold vast stretches of enemy territory and defeat Confederate armies to win.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln was not a military dictator and could fight only as long as the American public supported the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy sought to win independence by outlasting Lincoln; however, after Atlanta fell and Lincoln defeated McClellan in the election of 1864, hope for a political victory for the South ended.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln had secured the support of the Republicans, War Democrats, border states, emancipated slaves, and the neutrality of Britain and France.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] By defeating the Democrats and McClellan, he defeated the Copperheads, who had wanted a negotiated peace with the Confederacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Some scholars argue the Union held an insurmountable long-term advantage over the Confederacy in industrial strength and population.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate actions, they argue, only delayed defeat.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] A minority view among historians is that the Confederacy lost because, as E.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Merton Coulter put it, "people did not will hard enough and long enough to win".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] However, most historians reject the argument.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, after reading thousands of letters written by Confederate soldiers, found strong patriotism that continued to the end; they truly believed they were fighting for freedom and liberty.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Even as the Confederacy was visibly collapsing in 1864–65, most Confederate soldiers were fighting hard.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Also important were Lincoln's eloquence in articulating the national purpose and his skill in keeping the border states committed to the Union cause.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation was an effective use of the president's war powers.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate government failed to get Europe involved militarily.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Southern leaders needed to get European powers to help break the blockade the Union had created around Southern ports.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's naval blockade was 95 percent effective at stopping trade goods; as a result, imports and exports to the South declined significantly.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The abundance of European cotton and Britain's hostility to slavery, along with Lincoln's naval blockades, severely decreased any chance that Britain or France would enter the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Doyle has argued that the Union victory had a major impact on world history.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Union victory energized popular democratic forces.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] A Confederate victory, on the other hand, would have meant a new birth of slavery, not of freedom.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Scholars have debated what the effects of the war were on political and economic power in the South.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The prevailing view is that the southern planter elite retained its powerful position in the South.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] However, a 2017 study challenges this, noting that while some Southern elites retained their economic status, the turmoil of the 1860s created greater opportunities for economic mobility in the South, than in the North.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Exact casualty figures were collected for the Union, but Confederate records were poorly kept, or lost in the chaos of defeat.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Thus, the casualty figures are imprecise and based on statistical extrapolation.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Neither side kept a tally of civilian deaths due to the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] In the 19th century, the death toll had been estimated at a lower 620,000.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] In 2011, the death toll was recalculated based on a 1% sample of census data, yielding approximately 750,000 soldier deaths, 20 percent higher than traditionally estimated, and possibly as high as 850,000.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The figure was recalculated to 698,000 soldier deaths in 2024 after examining newly available full census records.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Mortality rates among men were as high as 19 percent in Louisiana, and 16.6–16.7 percent in Georgia and South Carolina respectively.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The war resulted in at least 1,030,000 casualties (3 percent of the population), including an estimated 698,000 soldier deaths—two-thirds by disease.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Based on 1860 census figures, 8 percent of all white men aged 13–43 died in the war, including 6 percent in the North and 18 percent in the South.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] About 56,000 soldiers died in prison camps during the War.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] An estimated 60,000 soldiers lost limbs.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] As McPherson notes, the war's "cost in American lives was as great as in all of the nation's other wars combined through Vietnam".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] In addition, there were 4,523 deaths in the Navy (2,112 in battle) and 460 in the Marines (148 in battle).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The US Colored Troops made up 10 percent of the Union death toll—15 percent of Union deaths from disease and less than 3 percent of those killed in battle.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Losses among African Americans were high.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] In the last year and a half and from all reported casualties, approximately 20 percent of all African Americans enrolled in the military died during the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Their mortality rate was significantly higher than white soldiers.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] While 15 percent of US Volunteers and just 9 percent of white Regular Army troops died, 21 percent of US Colored Troops died.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] While the figures of 360,000 army deaths for the Union and 260,000 for the Confederacy remained commonly cited, they are incomplete.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] This often happened only days or weeks later.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Francis Amasa Walker, superintendent of the 1870 census, used census and surgeon general data to estimate a minimum of 500,000 Union military deaths and 350,000 Confederate military deaths, a total of 850,000 soldiers.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] While Walker's estimates were originally dismissed because of the 1870 census's undercounting, it was later found that the census was only off by 6.5 percent and that the data Walker used would be roughly accurate.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Losses were far higher than during the war with Mexico, which saw roughly 13,000 American deaths, including fewer than two thousand killed in battle, between 1846 and 1848.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] One reason for the high number of battle deaths in the civil war was the continued use of tactics similar to those of the Napoleonic Wars, such as charging.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] With the advent of more accurate rifled barrels, Minié balls, and (near the end of the war for the Union) repeating firearms such as the Spencer repeating rifle and the Henry repeating rifle, soldiers were mowed down when standing in lines in the open.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] This led to the adoption of trench warfare, a style of fighting that defined much of World War I.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Deaths among former slaves has proven hard to estimate, due to the lack of reliable census data, though they were known to be considerable, as former slaves were set free or escaped in massive numbers in areas where the Union army did not have sufficient shelter, doctors, or food for them.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Professor Jim Downs states that tens of thousands to hundreds of thousands of slaves died during the war from disease, starvation, or exposure, and that if these deaths are counted in the war's total, the death toll would exceed 1 million.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that during the war, of the equines killed, including horses, mules, donkeys and even confiscated children's ponies, over 32,600 of them belonged to the Union and 45,800 the Confederacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] However, other estimates place the total at 1,000,000.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that 544 Confederate flags were captured during the war by the Union.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The flags were sent to the War Department in Washington.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Union flags captured by the Confederates were sent to Richmond.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Abolishing slavery was not a Union war goal from the outset but quickly became one.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln initially claimed that preserving the Union was the central goal.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] In contrast, the South fought to preserve slavery.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] While not all Southerners saw themselves as fighting for slavery, most officers and over a third of the rank and file in Lee's army had close family ties to slavery.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] To Northerners, the motivation was primarily to preserve the Union, not to abolish slavery.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's decision to issue the Proclamation angered Peace Democrats ("Copperheads") and War Democrats, but energized most Republicans.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] By warning that free blacks would flood the North, Democrats made gains in the 1862 elections, but they did not gain control of Congress.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Republicans' counterargument that slavery was the mainstay of the enemy steadily gained support, with the Democrats losing decisively in the 1863 elections in the Northern state of Ohio, when they tried to resurrect anti-black sentiment.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation legally freed the slaves in states "in rebellion", but, as a practical matter, slavery for the 3.5 million black people in the South effectively ended in each area when Union armies arrived.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The last Confederate slaves were freed on June 19, 1865, celebrated as the modern holiday of Juneteenth.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Slaves in the border states and those in some former Confederate territory occupied before the Emancipation Proclamation were freed by state action or (on December 6, 1865) by the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation enabled African Americans, both free blacks and escaped slaves, to join the Union Army.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] About 190,000 volunteered, further enhancing the numerical advantage the Union armies enjoyed over the Confederates, who did not dare emulate the equivalent manpower source for fear of undermining the legitimacy of slavery.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] During the war, sentiment concerning slaves, enslavement, and emancipation in the United States was divided.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's fears of making slavery a war issue were based on a harsh reality: abolition did not enjoy wide support in the west, the territories, and the border states.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] In 1861, Lincoln worried that premature attempts at emancipation would mean the loss of the border states, and that "to lose Kentucky is nearly the same as to lose the whole game".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Copperheads and some War Democrats opposed emancipation, although the latter eventually accepted it as part of the total war needed to save the Union.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln reversed attempts at emancipation by Secretary of War Simon Cameron and Generals John C.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont and David Hunter, in an effort to retain the loyalty of the border states and the War Democrats.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln warned the border states that a more radical type of emancipation would happen if they rejected his plan of gradual compensated emancipation and voluntary colonization.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] But compensated emancipation occurred only in the District of Columbia, where Congress had the power to enact it.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] When Lincoln told his cabinet about his proposed emancipation proclamation, which would apply to the states still in rebellion on January 1, 1863, Seward advised Lincoln to wait for a Union military victory before issuing it, because to do otherwise would seem like "our last shriek on the retreat".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Walter Stahr, however, writes, "There are contemporary sources, however, that suggest others were involved in the decision to delay", and Stahr quotes them.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] , who were fugitive slaves, including cooks, laundresses, laborers, teamsters, railroad repair crews, fled to the Union Army, but were not legally freed until the Emancipation Proclamation, which Lincoln signed on January 1, 1863, more than two years before the end of the Civil War.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] ; seen here are black and white teenaged soldiers who volunteered to fight for the Union.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln laid the groundwork for public support in an open letter published in response to Horace Greeley's "The Prayer of Twenty Millions"; the letter stated that Lincoln's goal was to save the Union, and that, if he freed the slaves, it would be as a means to that end.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] He also had a meeting at the White House with five African American representatives on August 14, 1862.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Arranging for a reporter to be present, he urged his visitors to agree to the voluntary colonization of black people.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's motive for both his letter to Greeley and his statement to the black visitors was apparently to make his forthcoming Emancipation Proclamation more palatable to racist white people.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] A Union victory in the Battle of Antietam on September 17, 1862, provided Lincoln with an opportunity to issue the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, and the War Governors' Conference added support for the proclamation.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln issued his preliminary Emancipation Proclamation on September 22, 1862.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] It stated that slaves in all states in rebellion on January 1, 1863, would be free.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] He issued his final Emancipation Proclamation on January 1, 1863, keeping his promise.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Hodges, Lincoln explained his belief that "If slavery is not wrong, nothing is wrong....
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] And yet I have never understood that the Presidency conferred upon me an unrestricted right to act officially upon this judgment and feeling....
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's moderate approach succeeded in inducing the border states to remain in the Union and War Democrats to support the Union.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The border states, which included Kentucky, Missouri, Maryland, Delaware, and Union-controlled regions around New Orleans, Norfolk, Virginia, and elsewhere, were not covered by the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Nor was Tennessee, which had come under Union control.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri and Maryland abolished slavery on their own; Kentucky and Delaware did not.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Still, the proclamation did not enjoy universal support.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] It caused much unrest in what were then considered western states, where racist sentiments led to a great fear of abolition.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] There was some concern that the proclamation would lead to the secession of western states, and its issuance prompted the stationing of Union troops in Illinois in case of rebellion.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] Since the Emancipation Proclamation was based on the president's war powers, it applied only in territory held by Confederates at the time it was issued.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Proclamation became a symbol of the Union's growing commitment to add emancipation to the Union's definition of liberty.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation greatly reduced the Confederacy's hope of being recognized or otherwise aided by Britain or France.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p02] By late 1864, Lincoln was playing a leading role in getting the House of Representatives to vote for the Thirteenth Amendment, which mandated the ending of chattel slavery.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The war devastated the South and posed serious questions of how it would be reintegrated into the Union.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The war destroyed much of the South's wealth, in part because wealth held in enslaved people (at least $1,000 each for a healthy adult prior to the war) was wiped off the books.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] All accumulated investment in Confederate bonds was forfeited; most banks and railroads were bankrupt.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The income per person dropped to less than 40 percent of that of the North, and that lasted into the 20th century.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Southern influence in the federal government, previously considerable, was greatly diminished until the second half of the 20th century.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Reconstruction began during the war, with the Emancipation Proclamation of January 1863, and it continued until 1877.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] From the Union perspective, the goals of Reconstruction were to consolidate victory by reuniting the Union, to guarantee a "republican form of government" for the ex-Confederate states, and to permanently end slavery—and prevent semi-slavery status.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] President Johnson, who took office in April 1865, took a lenient approach and saw the achievement of the main war goals as realized in 1865, when each ex-rebel state repudiated secession and ratified the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Radical Republicans demanded proof that Confederate nationalism was dead and that the slaves were truly free.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] They overrode Johnson's vetoes of civil rights legislation, and the House impeached him, although the Senate did not convict him.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] In 1868 and 1872, the Republican candidate Grant won the presidency.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] In 1872, the "Liberal Republicans" argued that the war goals had been achieved and Reconstruction should end.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] They chose Horace Greeley to head a presidential ticket in 1872 but were decisively defeated.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] In 1874, Democrats, primarily Southern, took control of Congress and opposed further reconstruction.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The Compromise of 1877 closed with a national consensus, except on the part of former slaves, that the war had finally ended.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] With the withdrawal of federal troops, however, white men retook control of every Southern legislature, and the Jim Crow era of disenfranchisement and legal segregation was ushered in.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The war had a demonstrable impact on American politics.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Many veterans on both sides were elected to political office, including five US presidents: Ulysses Grant, Rutherford B.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Garfield, Benjamin Harrison, and William McKinley.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The war is a central event in American collective memory.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] There are innumerable statues, commemorations, books, and archival collections.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The memory includes the home front, military affairs, the treatment of soldiers, both living and dead, in the war's aftermath, depictions of the war in literature and art, evaluations of heroes and villains, and considerations of the moral and political lessons of the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The last theme includes moral evaluations of racism and slavery, heroism and cowardice in combat and behind the lines, and issues of democracy and minority rights, as well as the notion of an "Empire of Liberty" influencing the world.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Historians have paid great attention to the causes of the war as well as to the war itself.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Military history has developed outside as well as inside academia, leading to a proliferation of studies by non-scholars who nevertheless are familiar with the primary sources and pay close attention to battles and campaigns and who write for the general public.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Practically every major figure in the war, both North and South, has had a serious biographical study.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Even the name used for the conflict has been controversial, with many names used for it.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] During and immediately after the war, Northern historians often used a term like "War of the Rebellion".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Writers in rebel states often referred to the "War for Southern Independence".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Some Southerners have described it as the "War of Northern Aggression".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The memory of the war in the white South crystallized in the myth of the "Lost Cause": that the Confederate cause was just and heroic.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The myth shaped regional identity and race relations for generations.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan notes that the Lost Cause was expressly a rationalization, a cover-up to vindicate the name and fame of those in rebellion.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Some claims revolve around the insignificance of slavery as a cause; some appeals highlight cultural differences between North and South; the military conflict by Confederate actors is idealized; in any case, secession was said to be lawful.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan argues that the adoption of the Lost Cause perspective facilitated the reunification of the North and the South while excusing the "virulent racism" of the 19th century, sacrificing black American progress to white man's reunification.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] He also deems the Lost Cause "a caricature of the truth.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] This caricature wholly misrepresents and distorts the facts of the matter" in every instance.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The Lost Cause myth was formalized by Charles A.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Beard, whose *The Rise of American Civilization* (1927) spawned Beardian historiography.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The Beards downplayed slavery, abolitionism, and issues of morality.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Though this interpretation was abandoned by the Beards in the 1940s, and by historians generally by the 1950s, Beardian themes still echo among Lost Cause writers.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The first efforts at Civil War battlefield preservation and memorialization came during the war, with the establishment of National Cemeteries at Gettysburg, Mill Springs and Chattanooga.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Soldiers began erecting markers on battlefields beginning with the First Battle of Bull Run in 1861.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The oldest surviving monument is the Hazen Brigade Monument near Murfreesboro in Central Tennessee, built in the summer of 1863 by soldiers in Union Col.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Hazen's brigade to mark the spot where they buried their dead, following the Battle of Stones River.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The Shiloh National Military Park was established in 1894 in Shiloh, Tennessee, followed by the Gettysburg National Military Park in 1895, and Vicksburg National Military Park in 1899.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] In 1933, these five parks and other national monuments were transferred to the National Park Service.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Chief among modern efforts to preserve Civil War sites has been the American Battlefield Trust, with more than 130 battlefields in 24 states.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The five major battlefield parks operated by the National Park Service had a combined 3 million visitors in 2018, down 70% from 10 million in 1970.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War has been commemorated in many ways, ranging from the reenactment of battles, to statues and memorial halls being erected, to films, and to stamps and coins with Civil War themes being issued, all of which helped to shape public memory.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] These commemorations occurred in greater numbers on the 100th and 150th anniversaries of the war.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Hollywood's take on the war has been especially influential in shaping public memory, as in such film classics as *The Birth of a Nation* (1915), *Gone with the Wind* (1939), and *Lincoln* (2012).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Ken Burns's PBS television series *The Civil War* (1990) is well-remembered, though criticized for its historical inaccuracy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Technological innovations during the war had a great impact on 19th-century science.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The war was an early example of an "industrial war", in which technological might is used to achieve military supremacy.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] New inventions, such as the train and telegraph, delivered soldiers, supplies and messages at a time when horses had been the fastest way to travel.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] It was also in this war that aerial warfare, in the form of reconnaissance balloons, was first used.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] It saw the first action involving steam-powered ironclad warships in naval warfare history.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] Repeating firearms such as the Henry rifle, Spencer repeating rifle, Colt revolving rifle, Triplett & Scott carbine and others, first appeared during the Civil War; they were a revolutionary invention that would soon replace muzzle-loading and single-shot firearms.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The war saw the first appearances of rapid-firing weapons and machine guns such as the Agar gun and Gatling gun.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War is one of the most studied events in American history, and the collection of cultural works around it is enormous.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-civil-war-p03] This section gives an abbreviated overview of the most notable works.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-flag-rugby] American flag rugby is divided up among four different levels based upon the grade level a child is entering.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-flag-rugby] Each division itself has a unique set of rules in recognition that there will be different ability levels between the various age groups.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-flag-rugby] The game, while based on rugby union, is actually far more related to rugby sevens.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-flag-rugby] Similarities are seen with the number of players on the field and the arrangement of the line-outs, scrums and kick-offs.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-flag-rugby] Like rugby union, games are played in halves but the halves are significantly reduced.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-flag-rugby] The halves are the same for all four levels at 10 minutes each instead of 40 minutes each.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-flag-rugby] The rule differences between each division are minor and gradually shift closer towards rugby union rules as the child advances up in divisions and increases his or her skill set.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-flag-rugby] For Owls the game typically revolves around teaching the children to run with the ball, learning to touch the ball down when scoring a try and learning basic passing skills.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-flag-rugby] Nothing is contested, there is no kicking, and there are no conversions.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-flag-rugby] However, when children reach the Eagle level, many of the prior mentioned restrictions are removed and the children play with contest are allowed open field kicking, and the game has a more dynamic flow to it.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-flag-rugby] The first iteration of American flag rugby was founded by Tom Feury in 1998.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-flag-rugby] Feury was initially looking for nothing more than a way to get his children and their friends introduced to the game.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-flag-rugby] In 1999, the town of Denville granted him access to a field in order to do so.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/american-flag-rugby] The first year began with only one team and 28 children.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] The teams alternate between "batting" (offensive role), sometimes called "in at bat" or simply *in*, and "fielding" (defensive role), also called "out in the field" or *out*.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Only the batting team may score, but teams have equal opportunities in both roles.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] The action starts when a player on the fielding team (the "bowler" or "pitcher") puts the ball in play with a delivery whose restriction depends on the game.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] A player on the batting team attempts to strike the delivered ball, commonly with a "bat", which is a club whose dimensions and other aspects are governed by the rules of the game.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] If the ball is not fairly delivered to the batter (i.e. not thrown within his reach), then penalties generally are awarded that help the batting team score.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] The batter generally has an obligation to hit certain balls that are delivered within his reach (i.e. balls aimed at a designated area, known as the strike zone or wicket), and must hit the ball so that it is not caught by a fielder before it touches the ground.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] The most desirable outcome for the batter is generally to hit the ball out of the field, as this results in automatically scoring runs; however, in certain bat-and-ball games, this can result in a penalty against the batter.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] If the ball is struck into the field, then the batter may become a runner trying to reach a safe haven or "base"/"ground".
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] While in contact with a base, the runner is "safe" from the fielding team and in a position to score runs.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Leaving a safe haven places the runner in danger of being put out (eliminated).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] The teams switch roles when the fielding team 'puts out'/'gets out' enough of the batting team's players, which varies by game.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] In modern baseball, the fielders put three *players* out.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] In cricket, they "dismiss" all players but one, though in some forms of cricket, there is a limit on the number of deliveries (scoring opportunities) that each team can have, such that the fielding team can become the batting team without getting anyone out.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Some games permit multiple runners and some have multiple bases to run in sequence.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Batting may occur, and running begin (and potentially end), at one of the bases.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] The movement between those "safe havens" is governed by the rules of the particular sport.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] The game ends when the losing team has completed the maximum number of innings (batting/scoring turns), which may range from 1 (as in limited-overs cricket) to 9 (as in baseball) or more.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Ties are generally broken (if at all) by allowing each team to have an additional turn to score.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Some variations of bat-and-ball games do not feature bats, with batters instead using parts of their bodies to hit the ball; these variations may also give the batter possession of the ball at the start of each play, eliminating the defensive team's role in starting the action.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] A prominent example of this is Baseball5, one of the main sporting disciplines governed by the World Baseball Softball Confederation along with baseball and softball.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] The history of baseball's formation and rise in popularity took place in England (potentially influenced by or descended from games played in continental Europe) and then America.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Predecessors of baseball were brought to America during the colonial era by English immigrants who played games similar to rounders; at the time, cricket was significantly more popular in the United States, since it was one of the main sports throughout the British Empire.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] However, the main format of cricket was first-class cricket, in which games lasted multiple days; baseball by comparison was a game that lasted less than two hours.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Because of the vast difference in the duration of the two sports and for other reasons, such as the rising American desire to have some type of national game distinct from England's games, baseball began to grow in America, especially among some of the non-English demographics.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Some attempts were made to nativize cricket in a way that would reduce its length and other perceived disadvantages relative to baseball; one example of this was wicket, an American variation of cricket which could be played in an afternoon.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] But by the time of the 1860s Civil War, baseball had begun to overtake cricket in popularity; one reason for this was that troops during the Civil War preferred to play baseball, as it did not require a specialized playing surface like the cricket pitch.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] After the Civil War, baseball became a much more organized sport than cricket in America, with more money and competition available to baseball players across the country; thus, several professional cricket players switched to playing baseball, and cricket faded away in America.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Baseball then began to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, supported by the contemporary westward expansion of the United States.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Over time, several variations of baseball appeared, with some being informal (kickball), others becoming professional sports in their own right (softball), and some even taking root overseas (pesäpallo).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] In other countries that were part of the British Empire, cricket slowly emerged as the game of choice for the colonizers to spread their culture and values among the colonized.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Some of the colonized people adapted to playing cricket in order to win the favor of the British, while in other cases, colonized peoples played cricket as a way of beating the British at their own sports, and thus proving themselves as equals.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] This helped to cement cricket as part of the national culture of several countries that later won their independence from the British.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] (right) have sped up baseball and cricket respectively, with the aim of attracting new fans.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] In 1971, the ODI (One Day International) format of cricket was first played internationally; the ODI format shortened cricket from a five-day long game (Test cricket) to a one-day long game.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] In 2003, a new format of cricket called T20 cricket emerged which was designed to last only about three hours.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] By this time, the average MLB game had gone from being two hours long to about three hours long, so the two sports now had formats that were of a comparable duration.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Later on, the T10 format of cricket, in which games last less than two hours, emerged at a domestic level, with leagues being started for it in several major cricket-playing countries.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] There is a great deal of variation among bat-and-ball games; for example, more runs are generally scored in a cricket match than dozens of baseball games combined, and while a T10 cricket match generally ends in 90 minutes, a Test cricket batter may bat for hours over several consecutive days.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] In cricket and baseball, the playing field is large (at the highest levels of each sport, the minimum distance between the two furthest ends of the field is about 400 to 500 feet (120 to 150 m)), and is divided into an infield and outfield (based on proximity to the batting area).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Cricket has the delivery and hitting of the ball done in the same area where the batters can run (the cricket pitch), while baseball does the running in a separate area.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Most bat-and-ball games have playing area in front of the batter (such as Schlagball), but may (like baseball) restrict batters from hitting the ball behind themselves or too far to the side; see foul territory.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Bat-and-ball sports can be modified to be played in an indoor court.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] For example, indoor cricket takes place in a 30 by 12 metres (98 ft × 39 ft) facility, while Baseball5 is played on a 21 metres (69 ft)-square field.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] In baseball-like games, the fielders (also known as "position players") operate in a standard set of baseball positions because it is generally possible to cover most of the field by spacing the fielders out in certain ways.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] By contrast, the significantly larger cricket field has many possible cricket fielding positions, with the 11 fielders occupying the slips cordon behind the batter, or other areas of the field.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] T20 cricket and baseball both last about 3 hours, while other forms of cricket can last either multiple days or less than three hours.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] In some bat-and-ball sports, there are team penalties designed to ensure the game goes at a faster pace.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] For example, in various formats of cricket, there are over rate penalties which kick in if a team has bowled too few deliveries within an allotted amount of time, while in some baseball leagues, there is a pitch clock that penalizes batters and pitchers for taking too much time between pitches.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] When one of the teams is not leading and only they have completed all of their allotted batting turns, this allows the other team to win automatically by surpassing the number of runs scored by the first team.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] In cricket, this situation is referred to as a "run chase", with the "target" of the batting team being the number of runs scored by the other team plus one.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] The result may also mention how many more times the losing team batted than the winning team.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] In some circumstances (e.g. bad weather), a complete game may not be possible in its originally envisioned timeframe because of weather or other reasons.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] In baseball-like games, which generally have many innings, it is possible to call the result of a game after both teams have batted only a few of their scheduled turns, or otherwise to finish/replay the game at a later date.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] In cricket, however, which is generally played to only one or two batting turns per team, a match may not be callable for the simple reason that only one of the teams has had the chance to score so far.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Bat-and-ball games can be played with modified rules in unorthodox places, such as in the street or the backyard.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Oftentimes, players are forbidden or penalized for hitting the ball out of the field into an area where it would be hard to reach, and play may be modified so as to ensure all players have an opportunity to participate, such as in Kwik cricket.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] At the international level, the World Baseball Classic is the premier baseball tournament.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] For cricket, the ODI World Cup, ICC T20 World Cup, and ICC World Test Championship are the premier tournaments.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] The Pesäpallo World Cup is played every 3 years.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] At the domestic level, baseball tends to be played in leagues with 2 major divisions, with the playoffs being contested in a best-of-seven format.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] T20 leagues in cricket tend to have 6 to 8 teams and follow the Page playoff system (two semi-finals, with an additional match played to determine which team enters the second semi-final, followed by a final).
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Gilli Danda (which is related to several other traditional games in other parts of the world) is a South Asian game with similarities to baseball and cricket.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] The aim of the game is for the batter to knock a stick on the ground up into the air using a stick held in the hand, and then to hit the airborne stick as far as possible.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] The batter is out if the stick is caught by a player on the other team before it touches the ground.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Points are earned either based on the distance the stick travels, or by the batter running to a designated area while the fielders collect the batted stick and throw it back to the hitting area to try to get the batter out.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] The game ends after each team has batted once, with each team batting until all of its players are out.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Striking the ball with a "bat" or any type of stick, or having the defensive team deliver the ball to the batter, is not crucial.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] These games use the foot or hand to hit the ball, and make it significantly easier to hit the ball overall, either by placing significant restrictions on the way the defensive team delivers the ball to the batter, or by giving the batter possession of the ball at the start of each play.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] Otherwise their rules may be similar or even identical to baseball or cricket.
[src:bat-and-ball-games/bat-and-ball-games-p01] The first two use a large (35 cm) soft ball.
